5349  TParams, Owned, IsDependent, ScopedEnumKWLoc,
5350  IsScopedUsingClassTag,
5351  BaseType, DSC == DeclSpecContext::DSC_type_specifier,
5352  DSC == DeclSpecContext::DSC_template_param ||
5353  DSC == DeclSpecContext::DSC_template_type_arg,
5354  OffsetOfState, &SkipBody).get();
5355 
5356  if (SkipBody.ShouldSkip) {
5357  assert(TUK == Sema::TUK_Definition && "can only skip a definition");
5358 
5359  BalancedDelimiterTracker T(*this, tok::l_brace);
5360  T.consumeOpen();
5361  T.skipToEnd();
5362 
5363  if (DS.SetTypeSpecType(DeclSpec::TST_enum, StartLoc,
5364  NameLoc.isValid() ? NameLoc : StartLoc,
5365  PrevSpec, DiagID, TagDecl, Owned,
5366  Actions.getASTContext().getPrintingPolicy()))
5367  Diag(StartLoc, DiagID) << PrevSpec;
5368  return;
5369  }
5370 
5371  if (IsDependent) {
5372  // This enum has a dependent nested-name-specifier. Handle it as a
5373  // dependent tag.
5374  if (!Name) {
5375  DS.SetTypeSpecError();
5376  Diag(Tok, diag::err_expected_type_name_after_typename);
5377  return;
5378  }
5379 
5380  TypeResult Type = Actions.ActOnDependentTag(
5381  getCurScope(), DeclSpec::TST_enum, TUK, SS, Name, StartLoc, NameLoc);
5382  if (Type.isInvalid()) {
5383  DS.SetTypeSpecError();
5384  return;
5385  }
5386 
5387  if (DS.SetTypeSpecType(DeclSpec::TST_typename, StartLoc,
5388  NameLoc.isValid() ? NameLoc : StartLoc,
5389  PrevSpec, DiagID, Type.get(),
5390  Actions.getASTContext().getPrintingPolicy()))
5391  Diag(StartLoc, DiagID) << PrevSpec;
5392 
5393  return;
5394  }
5395 
5396  if (!TagDecl) {
5397  // The action failed to produce an enumeration tag. If this is a
5398  // definition, consume the entire definition.
5399  if (Tok.is(tok::l_brace) && TUK != Sema::TUK_Reference) {
5400  ConsumeBrace();
5401  SkipUntil(tok::r_brace, StopAtSemi);
5402  }
5403 
5404  DS.SetTypeSpecError();
5405  return;
5406  }
5407 
5408  if (Tok.is(tok::l_brace) && TUK == Sema::TUK_Definition) {
5409  Decl *D = SkipBody.CheckSameAsPrevious ? SkipBody.New : TagDecl;
5410  ParseEnumBody(StartLoc, D);
5411  if (SkipBody.CheckSameAsPrevious &&
5412  !Actions.ActOnDuplicateDefinition(TagDecl, SkipBody)) {
5413  DS.SetTypeSpecError();
5414  return;
5415  }
5416  }
5417 
5418  if (DS.SetTypeSpecType(DeclSpec::TST_enum, StartLoc,
5419  NameLoc.isValid() ? NameLoc : StartLoc,
5420  PrevSpec, DiagID, TagDecl, Owned,
5421  Actions.getASTContext().getPrintingPolicy()))
5422  Diag(StartLoc, DiagID) << PrevSpec;
5423 }
5424 
5425 /// ParseEnumBody - Parse a {} enclosed enumerator-list.
5426 /// enumerator-list:
5427 /// enumerator
5428 /// enumerator-list ',' enumerator
5429 /// enumerator:
5430 /// enumeration-constant attributes[opt]
5431 /// enumeration-constant attributes[opt] '=' constant-expression
5432 /// enumeration-constant:
5433 /// identifier
5434 ///
5435 void Parser::ParseEnumBody(SourceLocation StartLoc, Decl *EnumDecl) {
5436  // Enter the scope of the enum body and start the definition.
5437  ParseScope EnumScope(this, Scope::DeclScope | Scope::EnumScope);
5438  Actions.ActOnTagStartDefinition(getCurScope(), EnumDecl);
5439 
5440  BalancedDelimiterTracker T(*this, tok::l_brace);
5441  T.consumeOpen();
5442 
5443  // C does not allow an empty enumerator-list, C++ does [dcl.enum].
5444  if (Tok.is(tok::r_brace) && !getLangOpts().CPlusPlus)
5445  Diag(Tok, diag::err_empty_enum);
5446 
5447  SmallVector<Decl *, 32> EnumConstantDecls;
5448  SmallVector<SuppressAccessChecks, 32> EnumAvailabilityDiags;
5449 
5450  Decl *LastEnumConstDecl = nullptr;
5451 
5452  // Parse the enumerator-list.
5453  while (Tok.isNot(tok::r_brace)) {
5454  // Parse enumerator. If failed, try skipping till the start of the next
5455  // enumerator definition.
5456  if (Tok.isNot(tok::identifier)) {
5457  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), diag::err_expected) << tok::identifier;
5458  if (SkipUntil(tok::comma, tok::r_brace, StopBeforeMatch) &&
5459  TryConsumeToken(tok::comma))
5460  continue;
5461  break;
5462  }
5463  IdentifierInfo *Ident = Tok.getIdentifierInfo();
5464  SourceLocation IdentLoc = ConsumeToken();
5465 
5466  // If attributes exist after the enumerator, parse them.
5467  ParsedAttributes attrs(AttrFactory);
5468  MaybeParseGNUAttributes(attrs);
5469  if (isAllowedCXX11AttributeSpecifier()) {
5470  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus)
5471  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17
5472  ? diag::warn_cxx14_compat_ns_enum_attribute
5473  : diag::ext_ns_enum_attribute)
5474  << 1 /*enumerator*/;
5475  ParseCXX11Attributes(attrs);
5476  }
5477 
5478  SourceLocation EqualLoc;
5479  ExprResult AssignedVal;
5480  EnumAvailabilityDiags.emplace_back(*this);
5481 
5482  EnterExpressionEvaluationContext ConstantEvaluated(
5483  Actions, Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContext::ConstantEvaluated);
5484  if (TryConsumeToken(tok::equal, EqualLoc)) {
5485  AssignedVal = ParseConstantExpressionInExprEvalContext();
5486  if (AssignedVal.isInvalid())
5487  SkipUntil(tok::comma, tok::r_brace, StopBeforeMatch);
5488  }
5489 
5490  // Install the enumerator constant into EnumDecl.
5491  Decl *EnumConstDecl = Actions.ActOnEnumConstant(
5492  getCurScope(), EnumDecl, LastEnumConstDecl, IdentLoc, Ident, attrs,
5493  EqualLoc, AssignedVal.get());
5494  EnumAvailabilityDiags.back().done();
5495 
5496  EnumConstantDecls.push_back(EnumConstDecl);
5497  LastEnumConstDecl = EnumConstDecl;
5498 
5499  if (Tok.is(tok::identifier)) {
5500  // We're missing a comma between enumerators.
5501  SourceLocation Loc = getEndOfPreviousToken();
5502  Diag(Loc, diag::err_enumerator_list_missing_comma)
5503  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(Loc, ", ");
5504  continue;
5505  }
5506 
5507  // Emumerator definition must be finished, only comma or r_brace are
5508  // allowed here.
5509  SourceLocation CommaLoc;
5510  if (Tok.isNot(tok::r_brace) && !TryConsumeToken(tok::comma, CommaLoc)) {
5511  if (EqualLoc.isValid())
5512  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), diag::err_expected_either) << tok::r_brace
5513  << tok::comma;
5514  else
5515  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), diag::err_expected_end_of_enumerator);
5516  if (SkipUntil(tok::comma, tok::r_brace, StopBeforeMatch)) {
5517  if (TryConsumeToken(tok::comma, CommaLoc))
5518  continue;
5519  } else {
5520  break;
5521  }
5522  }
5523 
5524  // If comma is followed by r_brace, emit appropriate warning.
5525  if (Tok.is(tok::r_brace) && CommaLoc.isValid()) {
5526  if (!getLangOpts().C99 && !getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11)
5527  Diag(CommaLoc, getLangOpts().CPlusPlus ?
5528  diag::ext_enumerator_list_comma_cxx :
5529  diag::ext_enumerator_list_comma_c)
5530  << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(CommaLoc);
5531  else if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11)
5532  Diag(CommaLoc, diag::warn_cxx98_compat_enumerator_list_comma)
5533  << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(CommaLoc);
5534  break;
5535  }
5536  }
5537 
5538  // Eat the }.
5539  T.consumeClose();
5540 
5541  // If attributes exist after the identifier list, parse them.
5542  ParsedAttributes attrs(AttrFactory);
5543  MaybeParseGNUAttributes(attrs);
5544 
5545  Actions.ActOnEnumBody(StartLoc, T.getRange(), EnumDecl, EnumConstantDecls,
5546  getCurScope(), attrs);
5547 
5548  // Now handle enum constant availability diagnostics.
5549  assert(EnumConstantDecls.size() == EnumAvailabilityDiags.size());
5550  for (size_t i = 0, e = EnumConstantDecls.size(); i != e; ++i) {
5551  ParsingDeclRAIIObject PD(*this, ParsingDeclRAIIObject::NoParent);
5552  EnumAvailabilityDiags[i].redelay();
5553  PD.complete(EnumConstantDecls[i]);
5554  }
5555 
5556  EnumScope.Exit();
5557  Actions.ActOnTagFinishDefinition(getCurScope(), EnumDecl, T.getRange());
5558 
5559  // The next token must be valid after an enum definition. If not, a ';'
5560  // was probably forgotten.
5561  bool CanBeBitfield = getCurScope()->isClassScope();
5562  if (!isValidAfterTypeSpecifier(CanBeBitfield)) {
5563  ExpectAndConsume(tok::semi, diag::err_expected_after, "enum");
5564  // Push this token back into the preprocessor and change our current token
5565  // to ';' so that the rest of the code recovers as though there were an
5566  // ';' after the definition.
5567  PP.EnterToken(Tok, /*IsReinject=*/true);
5568  Tok.setKind(tok::semi);
5569  }
5570 }
5571 
5572 /// isKnownToBeTypeSpecifier - Return true if we know that the specified token
5573 /// is definitely a type-specifier. Return false if it isn't part of a type
5574 /// specifier or if we're not sure.
5575 bool Parser::isKnownToBeTypeSpecifier(const Token &Tok) const {
5576  switch (Tok.getKind()) {
5577  default: return false;
5578  // type-specifiers
5579  case tok::kw_short:
5580  case tok::kw_long:
5581  case tok::kw___int64:
5582  case tok::kw___int128:
5583  case tok::kw_signed:
5584  case tok::kw_unsigned:
5585  case tok::kw__Complex:
5586  case tok::kw__Imaginary:
5587  case tok::kw_void:
5588  case tok::kw_char:
5589  case tok::kw_wchar_t:
5590  case tok::kw_char8_t:
5591  case tok::kw_char16_t:
5592  case tok::kw_char32_t:
5593  case tok::kw_int:
5594  case tok::kw__ExtInt:
5595  case tok::kw__BitInt:
5596  case tok::kw___bf16:
5597  case tok::kw_half:
5598  case tok::kw_float:
5599  case tok::kw_double:
5600  case tok::kw__Accum:
5601  case tok::kw__Fract:
5602  case tok::kw__Float16:
5603  case tok::kw___float128:
5604  case tok::kw___ibm128:
5605  case tok::kw_bool:
5606  case tok::kw__Bool:
5607  case tok::kw__Decimal32:
5608  case tok::kw__Decimal64:
5609  case tok::kw__Decimal128:
5610  case tok::kw___vector:
5611 #define GENERIC_IMAGE_TYPE(ImgType, Id) case tok::kw_##ImgType##_t:
5612 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLImageTypes.def"
5613 
5614  // struct-or-union-specifier (C99) or class-specifier (C++)
5615  case tok::kw_class:
5616  case tok::kw_struct:
5617  case tok::kw___interface:
5618  case tok::kw_union:
5619  // enum-specifier
5620  case tok::kw_enum:
5621 
5622  // typedef-name
5623  case tok::annot_typename:
5624  return true;
5625  }
5626 }
5627 
5628 /// isTypeSpecifierQualifier - Return true if the current token could be the
5629 /// start of a specifier-qualifier-list.
5630 bool Parser::isTypeSpecifierQualifier() {
5631  switch (Tok.getKind()) {
5632  default: return false;
5633 
5634  case tok::identifier: // foo::bar
5635  if (TryAltiVecVectorToken())
5636  return true;
5637  [[fallthrough]];
5638  case tok::kw_typename: // typename T::type
5639  // Annotate typenames and C++ scope specifiers. If we get one, just
5640  // recurse to handle whatever we get.
5641  if (TryAnnotateTypeOrScopeToken())
5642  return true;
5643  if (Tok.is(tok::identifier))
5644  return false;
5645  return isTypeSpecifierQualifier();
5646 
5647  case tok::coloncolon: // ::foo::bar
5648  if (NextToken().is(tok::kw_new) || // ::new
5649  NextToken().is(tok::kw_delete)) // ::delete
5650  return false;
5651 
5652  if (TryAnnotateTypeOrScopeToken())
5653  return true;
5654  return isTypeSpecifierQualifier();
5655 
5656  // GNU attributes support.
5657  case tok::kw___attribute:
5658  // C23/GNU typeof support.
5659  case tok::kw_typeof:
5660  case tok::kw_typeof_unqual:
5661 
5662  // type-specifiers
5663  case tok::kw_short:
5664  case tok::kw_long:
5665  case tok::kw___int64:
5666  case tok::kw___int128:
5667  case tok::kw_signed:
5668  case tok::kw_unsigned:
5669  case tok::kw__Complex:
5670  case tok::kw__Imaginary:
5671  case tok::kw_void:
5672  case tok::kw_char:
5673  case tok::kw_wchar_t:
5674  case tok::kw_char8_t:
5675  case tok::kw_char16_t:
5676  case tok::kw_char32_t:
5677  case tok::kw_int:
5678  case tok::kw__ExtInt:
5679  case tok::kw__BitInt:
5680  case tok::kw_half:
5681  case tok::kw___bf16:
5682  case tok::kw_float:
5683  case tok::kw_double:
5684  case tok::kw__Accum:
5685  case tok::kw__Fract:
5686  case tok::kw__Float16:
5687  case tok::kw___float128:
5688  case tok::kw___ibm128:
5689  case tok::kw_bool:
5690  case tok::kw__Bool:
5691  case tok::kw__Decimal32:
5692  case tok::kw__Decimal64:
5693  case tok::kw__Decimal128:
5694  case tok::kw___vector:
5695 #define GENERIC_IMAGE_TYPE(ImgType, Id) case tok::kw_##ImgType##_t:
5696 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLImageTypes.def"
5697 
5698  // struct-or-union-specifier (C99) or class-specifier (C++)
5699  case tok::kw_class:
5700  case tok::kw_struct:
5701  case tok::kw___interface:
5702  case tok::kw_union:
5703  // enum-specifier
5704  case tok::kw_enum:
5705 
5706  // type-qualifier
5707  case tok::kw_const:
5708  case tok::kw_volatile:
5709  case tok::kw_restrict:
5710  case tok::kw__Sat:
5711 
5712  // Debugger support.
5713  case tok::kw___unknown_anytype:
5714 
5715  // typedef-name
5716  case tok::annot_typename:
5717  return true;
5718 
5719  // GNU ObjC bizarre protocol extension: <proto1,proto2> with implicit 'id'.
5720  case tok::less:
5721  return getLangOpts().ObjC;
5722 
5723  case tok::kw___cdecl:
5724  case tok::kw___stdcall:
5725  case tok::kw___fastcall:
5726  case tok::kw___thiscall:
5727  case tok::kw___regcall:
5728  case tok::kw___vectorcall:
5729  case tok::kw___w64:
5730  case tok::kw___ptr64:
5731  case tok::kw___ptr32:
5732  case tok::kw___pascal:
5733  case tok::kw___unaligned:
5734 
5735  case tok::kw__Nonnull:
5736  case tok::kw__Nullable:
5737  case tok::kw__Nullable_result:
5738  case tok::kw__Null_unspecified:
5739 
5740  case tok::kw___kindof:
5741 
5742  case tok::kw___private:
5743  case tok::kw___local:
5744  case tok::kw___global:
5745  case tok::kw___constant:
5746  case tok::kw___generic:
5747  case tok::kw___read_only:
5748  case tok::kw___read_write:
5749  case tok::kw___write_only:
5750  case tok::kw___funcref:
5751  return true;
5752 
5753  case tok::kw_private:
5754  return getLangOpts().OpenCL;
5755 
5756  // C11 _Atomic
5757  case tok::kw__Atomic:
5758  return true;
5759 
5760  // HLSL type qualifiers
5761  case tok::kw_groupshared:
5762  case tok::kw_in:
5763  case tok::kw_inout:
5764  case tok::kw_out:
5765  return getLangOpts().HLSL;
5766  }
5767 }
5768 
5769 Parser::DeclGroupPtrTy Parser::ParseTopLevelStmtDecl() {
5770  assert(PP.isIncrementalProcessingEnabled() && "Not in incremental mode");
5771 
5772  // Parse a top-level-stmt.
5773  Parser::StmtVector Stmts;
5774  ParsedStmtContext SubStmtCtx = ParsedStmtContext();
5775  ParseScope FnScope(this, Scope::FnScope | Scope::DeclScope |
5776  Scope::CompoundStmtScope);
5777  TopLevelStmtDecl *TLSD = Actions.ActOnStartTopLevelStmtDecl(getCurScope());
5778  StmtResult R = ParseStatementOrDeclaration(Stmts, SubStmtCtx);
5779  if (!R.isUsable())
5780  return nullptr;
5781 
5782  Actions.ActOnFinishTopLevelStmtDecl(TLSD, R.get());
5783 
5784  if (Tok.is(tok::annot_repl_input_end) &&
5785  Tok.getAnnotationValue() != nullptr) {
5786  ConsumeAnnotationToken();
5787  TLSD->setSemiMissing();
5788  }
5789 
5790  SmallVector<Decl *, 2> DeclsInGroup;
5791  DeclsInGroup.push_back(TLSD);
5792 
5793  // Currently happens for things like -fms-extensions and use `__if_exists`.
5794  for (Stmt *S : Stmts) {
5795  // Here we should be safe as `__if_exists` and friends are not introducing
5796  // new variables which need to live outside file scope.
5797  TopLevelStmtDecl *D = Actions.ActOnStartTopLevelStmtDecl(getCurScope());
5798  Actions.ActOnFinishTopLevelStmtDecl(D, S);
5799  DeclsInGroup.push_back(D);
5800  }
5801 
5802  return Actions.BuildDeclaratorGroup(DeclsInGroup);
5803 }
5804 
5805 /// isDeclarationSpecifier() - Return true if the current token is part of a
5806 /// declaration specifier.
5807 ///
5808 /// \param AllowImplicitTypename whether this is a context where T::type [T
5809 /// dependent] can appear.
5810 /// \param DisambiguatingWithExpression True to indicate that the purpose of
5811 /// this check is to disambiguate between an expression and a declaration.
5812 bool Parser::isDeclarationSpecifier(
5813  ImplicitTypenameContext AllowImplicitTypename,
5814  bool DisambiguatingWithExpression) {
5815  switch (Tok.getKind()) {
5816  default: return false;
5817 
5818  // OpenCL 2.0 and later define this keyword.
5819  case tok::kw_pipe:
5820  return getLangOpts().OpenCL &&
5821  getLangOpts().getOpenCLCompatibleVersion() >= 200;
5822 
5823  case tok::identifier: // foo::bar
5824  // Unfortunate hack to support "Class.factoryMethod" notation.
5825  if (getLangOpts().ObjC && NextToken().is(tok::period))
5826  return false;
5827  if (TryAltiVecVectorToken())
5828  return true;
5829  [[fallthrough]];
5830  case tok::kw_decltype: // decltype(T())::type
5831  case tok::kw_typename: // typename T::type
5832  // Annotate typenames and C++ scope specifiers. If we get one, just
5833  // recurse to handle whatever we get.
5834  if (TryAnnotateTypeOrScopeToken(AllowImplicitTypename))
5835  return true;
5836  if (TryAnnotateTypeConstraint())
5837  return true;
5838  if (Tok.is(tok::identifier))
5839  return false;
5840 
5841  // If we're in Objective-C and we have an Objective-C class type followed
5842  // by an identifier and then either ':' or ']', in a place where an
5843  // expression is permitted, then this is probably a class message send
5844  // missing the initial '['. In this case, we won't consider this to be
5845  // the start of a declaration.
5846  if (DisambiguatingWithExpression &&
5847  isStartOfObjCClassMessageMissingOpenBracket())
5848  return false;
5849 
5850  return isDeclarationSpecifier(AllowImplicitTypename);
5851 
5852  case tok::coloncolon: // ::foo::bar
5853  if (!getLangOpts().CPlusPlus)
5854  return false;
5855  if (NextToken().is(tok::kw_new) || // ::new
5856  NextToken().is(tok::kw_delete)) // ::delete
5857  return false;
5858 
5859  // Annotate typenames and C++ scope specifiers. If we get one, just
5860  // recurse to handle whatever we get.
5861  if (TryAnnotateTypeOrScopeToken())
5862  return true;
5863  return isDeclarationSpecifier(ImplicitTypenameContext::No);
5864 
5865  // storage-class-specifier
5866  case tok::kw_typedef:
5867  case tok::kw_extern:
5868  case tok::kw___private_extern__:
5869  case tok::kw_static:
5870  case tok::kw_auto:
5871  case tok::kw___auto_type:
5872  case tok::kw_register:
5873  case tok::kw___thread:
5874  case tok::kw_thread_local:
5875  case tok::kw__Thread_local:
5876 
5877  // Modules
5878  case tok::kw___module_private__:
5879 
5880  // Debugger support
5881  case tok::kw___unknown_anytype:
5882 
5883  // type-specifiers
5884  case tok::kw_short:
5885  case tok::kw_long:
5886  case tok::kw___int64:
5887  case tok::kw___int128:
5888  case tok::kw_signed:
5889  case tok::kw_unsigned:
5890  case tok::kw__Complex:
5891  case tok::kw__Imaginary:
5892  case tok::kw_void:
5893  case tok::kw_char:
5894  case tok::kw_wchar_t:
5895  case tok::kw_char8_t:
5896  case tok::kw_char16_t:
5897  case tok::kw_char32_t:
5898 
5899  case tok::kw_int:
5900  case tok::kw__ExtInt:
5901  case tok::kw__BitInt:
5902  case tok::kw_half:
5903  case tok::kw___bf16:
5904  case tok::kw_float:
5905  case tok::kw_double:
5906  case tok::kw__Accum:
5907  case tok::kw__Fract:
5908  case tok::kw__Float16:
5909  case tok::kw___float128:
5910  case tok::kw___ibm128:
5911  case tok::kw_bool:
5912  case tok::kw__Bool:
5913  case tok::kw__Decimal32:
5914  case tok::kw__Decimal64:
5915  case tok::kw__Decimal128:
5916  case tok::kw___vector:
5917 
5918  // struct-or-union-specifier (C99) or class-specifier (C++)
5919  case tok::kw_class:
5920  case tok::kw_struct:
5921  case tok::kw_union:
5922  case tok::kw___interface:
5923  // enum-specifier
5924  case tok::kw_enum:
5925 
5926  // type-qualifier
5927  case tok::kw_const:
5928  case tok::kw_volatile:
5929  case tok::kw_restrict:
5930  case tok::kw__Sat:
5931 
5932  // function-specifier
5933  case tok::kw_inline:
5934  case tok::kw_virtual:
5935  case tok::kw_explicit:
5936  case tok::kw__Noreturn:
5937 
5938  // alignment-specifier
5939  case tok::kw__Alignas:
5940 
5941  // friend keyword.
5942  case tok::kw_friend:
5943 
5944  // static_assert-declaration
5945  case tok::kw_static_assert:
5946  case tok::kw__Static_assert:
5947 
5948  // C23/GNU typeof support.
5949  case tok::kw_typeof:
5950  case tok::kw_typeof_unqual:
5951 
5952  // GNU attributes.
5953  case tok::kw___attribute:
5954 
5955  // C++11 decltype and constexpr.
5956  case tok::annot_decltype:
5957  case tok::annot_pack_indexing_type:
5958  case tok::kw_constexpr:
5959 
5960  // C++20 consteval and constinit.
5961  case tok::kw_consteval:
5962  case tok::kw_constinit:
5963 
5964  // C11 _Atomic
5965  case tok::kw__Atomic:
5966  return true;
5967 
5968  case tok::kw_alignas:
5969  // alignas is a type-specifier-qualifier in C23, which is a kind of
5970  // declaration-specifier. Outside of C23 mode (including in C++), it is not.
5971  return getLangOpts().C23;
5972 
5973  // GNU ObjC bizarre protocol extension: <proto1,proto2> with implicit 'id'.
5974  case tok::less:
5975  return getLangOpts().ObjC;
5976 
5977  // typedef-name
5978  case tok::annot_typename:
5979  return !DisambiguatingWithExpression ||
5980  !isStartOfObjCClassMessageMissingOpenBracket();
5981 
5982  // placeholder-type-specifier
5983  case tok::annot_template_id: {
5984  TemplateIdAnnotation *TemplateId = takeTemplateIdAnnotation(Tok);
5985  if (TemplateId->hasInvalidName())
5986  return true;
5987  // FIXME: What about type templates that have only been annotated as
5988  // annot_template_id, not as annot_typename?
5989  return isTypeConstraintAnnotation() &&
5990  (NextToken().is(tok::kw_auto) || NextToken().is(tok::kw_decltype));
5991  }
5992 
5993  case tok::annot_cxxscope: {
5994  TemplateIdAnnotation *TemplateId =
5995  NextToken().is(tok::annot_template_id)
5996  ? takeTemplateIdAnnotation(NextToken())
5997  : nullptr;
5998  if (TemplateId && TemplateId->hasInvalidName())
5999  return true;
6000  // FIXME: What about type templates that have only been annotated as
6001  // annot_template_id, not as annot_typename?
6002  if (NextToken().is(tok::identifier) && TryAnnotateTypeConstraint())
6003  return true;
6004  return isTypeConstraintAnnotation() &&
6005  GetLookAheadToken(2).isOneOf(tok::kw_auto, tok::kw_decltype);
6006  }
6007 
6008  case tok::kw___declspec:
6009  case tok::kw___cdecl:
6010  case tok::kw___stdcall:
6011  case tok::kw___fastcall:
6012  case tok::kw___thiscall:
6013  case tok::kw___regcall:
6014  case tok::kw___vectorcall:
6015  case tok::kw___w64:
6016  case tok::kw___sptr:
6017  case tok::kw___uptr:
6018  case tok::kw___ptr64:
6019  case tok::kw___ptr32:
6020  case tok::kw___forceinline:
6021  case tok::kw___pascal:
6022  case tok::kw___unaligned:
6023 
6024  case tok::kw__Nonnull:
6025  case tok::kw__Nullable:
6026  case tok::kw__Nullable_result:
6027  case tok::kw__Null_unspecified:
6028 
6029  case tok::kw___kindof:
6030 
6031  case tok::kw___private:
6032  case tok::kw___local:
6033  case tok::kw___global:
6034  case tok::kw___constant:
6035  case tok::kw___generic:
6036  case tok::kw___read_only:
6037  case tok::kw___read_write:
6038  case tok::kw___write_only:
6039 #define GENERIC_IMAGE_TYPE(ImgType, Id) case tok::kw_##ImgType##_t:
6040 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLImageTypes.def"
6041 
6042  case tok::kw___funcref:
6043  case tok::kw_groupshared:
6044  return true;
6045 
6046  case tok::kw_private:
6047  return getLangOpts().OpenCL;
6048  }
6049 }
6050 
6051 bool Parser::isConstructorDeclarator(bool IsUnqualified, bool DeductionGuide,
6052  DeclSpec::FriendSpecified IsFriend,
6053  const ParsedTemplateInfo *TemplateInfo) {
6054  RevertingTentativeParsingAction TPA(*this);
6055  // Parse the C++ scope specifier.
6056  CXXScopeSpec SS;
6057  if (TemplateInfo && TemplateInfo->TemplateParams)
6058  SS.setTemplateParamLists(*TemplateInfo->TemplateParams);
6059 
6060  if (ParseOptionalCXXScopeSpecifier(SS, /*ObjectType=*/nullptr,
6061  /*ObjectHasErrors=*/false,
6062  /*EnteringContext=*/true)) {
6063  return false;
6064  }
6065 
6066  // Parse the constructor name.
6067  if (Tok.is(tok::identifier)) {
6068  // We already know that we have a constructor name; just consume
6069  // the token.
6070  ConsumeToken();
6071  } else if (Tok.is(tok::annot_template_id)) {
6072  ConsumeAnnotationToken();
6073  } else {
6074  return false;
6075  }
6076 
6077  // There may be attributes here, appertaining to the constructor name or type
6078  // we just stepped past.
6079  SkipCXX11Attributes();
6080 
6081  // Current class name must be followed by a left parenthesis.
6082  if (Tok.isNot(tok::l_paren)) {
6083  return false;
6084  }
6085  ConsumeParen();
6086 
6087  // A right parenthesis, or ellipsis followed by a right parenthesis signals
6088  // that we have a constructor.
6089  if (Tok.is(tok::r_paren) ||
6090  (Tok.is(tok::ellipsis) && NextToken().is(tok::r_paren))) {
6091  return true;
6092  }
6093 
6094  // A C++11 attribute here signals that we have a constructor, and is an
6095  // attribute on the first constructor parameter.
6096  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 &&
6097  isCXX11AttributeSpecifier(/*Disambiguate*/ false,
6098  /*OuterMightBeMessageSend*/ true)) {
6099  return true;
6100  }
6101 
6102  // If we need to, enter the specified scope.
6103  DeclaratorScopeObj DeclScopeObj(*this, SS);
6104  if (SS.isSet() && Actions.ShouldEnterDeclaratorScope(getCurScope(), SS))
6105  DeclScopeObj.EnterDeclaratorScope();
6106 
6107  // Optionally skip Microsoft attributes.
6108  ParsedAttributes Attrs(AttrFactory);
6109  MaybeParseMicrosoftAttributes(Attrs);
6110 
6111  // Check whether the next token(s) are part of a declaration
6112  // specifier, in which case we have the start of a parameter and,
6113  // therefore, we know that this is a constructor.
6114  // Due to an ambiguity with implicit typename, the above is not enough.
6115  // Additionally, check to see if we are a friend.
6116  // If we parsed a scope specifier as well as friend,
6117  // we might be parsing a friend constructor.
6118  bool IsConstructor = false;
6119  ImplicitTypenameContext ITC = IsFriend && !SS.isSet()
6120  ? ImplicitTypenameContext::No
6121  : ImplicitTypenameContext::Yes;
6122  // Constructors cannot have this parameters, but we support that scenario here
6123  // to improve diagnostic.
6124  if (Tok.is(tok::kw_this)) {
6125  ConsumeToken();
6126  return isDeclarationSpecifier(ITC);
6127  }
6128 
6129  if (isDeclarationSpecifier(ITC))
6130  IsConstructor = true;
6131  else if (Tok.is(tok::identifier) ||
6132  (Tok.is(tok::annot_cxxscope) && NextToken().is(tok::identifier))) {
6133  // We've seen "C ( X" or "C ( X::Y", but "X" / "X::Y" is not a type.
6134  // This might be a parenthesized member name, but is more likely to
6135  // be a constructor declaration with an invalid argument type. Keep
6136  // looking.
6137  if (Tok.is(tok::annot_cxxscope))
6138  ConsumeAnnotationToken();
6139  ConsumeToken();
6140 
6141  // If this is not a constructor, we must be parsing a declarator,
6142  // which must have one of the following syntactic forms (see the
6143  // grammar extract at the start of ParseDirectDeclarator):
6144  switch (Tok.getKind()) {
6145  case tok::l_paren:
6146  // C(X ( int));
6147  case tok::l_square:
6148  // C(X [ 5]);
6149  // C(X [ [attribute]]);
6150  case tok::coloncolon:
6151  // C(X :: Y);
6152  // C(X :: *p);
6153  // Assume this isn't a constructor, rather than assuming it's a
6154  // constructor with an unnamed parameter of an ill-formed type.
6155  break;
6156 
6157  case tok::r_paren:
6158  // C(X )
6159 
6160  // Skip past the right-paren and any following attributes to get to
6161  // the function body or trailing-return-type.
6162  ConsumeParen();
6163  SkipCXX11Attributes();
6164 
6165  if (DeductionGuide) {
6166  // C(X) -> ... is a deduction guide.
6167  IsConstructor = Tok.is(tok::arrow);
6168  break;
6169  }
6170  if (Tok.is(tok::colon) || Tok.is(tok::kw_try)) {
6171  // Assume these were meant to be constructors:
6172  // C(X) : (the name of a bit-field cannot be parenthesized).
6173  // C(X) try (this is otherwise ill-formed).
6174  IsConstructor = true;
6175  }
6176  if (Tok.is(tok::semi) || Tok.is(tok::l_brace)) {
6177  // If we have a constructor name within the class definition,
6178  // assume these were meant to be constructors:
6179  // C(X) {
6180  // C(X) ;
6181  // ... because otherwise we would be declaring a non-static data
6182  // member that is ill-formed because it's of the same type as its
6183  // surrounding class.
6184  //
6185  // FIXME: We can actually do this whether or not the name is qualified,
6186  // because if it is qualified in this context it must be being used as
6187  // a constructor name.
6188  // currently, so we're somewhat conservative here.
6189  IsConstructor = IsUnqualified;
6190  }
6191  break;
6192 
6193  default:
6194  IsConstructor = true;
6195  break;
6196  }
6197  }
6198  return IsConstructor;
6199 }
6200 
6201 /// ParseTypeQualifierListOpt
6202 /// type-qualifier-list: [C99 6.7.5]
6203 /// type-qualifier
6204 /// [vendor] attributes
6205 /// [ only if AttrReqs & AR_VendorAttributesParsed ]
6206 /// type-qualifier-list type-qualifier
6207 /// [vendor] type-qualifier-list attributes
6208 /// [ only if AttrReqs & AR_VendorAttributesParsed ]
6209 /// [C++0x] attribute-specifier[opt] is allowed before cv-qualifier-seq
6210 /// [ only if AttReqs & AR_CXX11AttributesParsed ]
6211 /// Note: vendor can be GNU, MS, etc and can be explicitly controlled via
6212 /// AttrRequirements bitmask values.
6213 void Parser::ParseTypeQualifierListOpt(
6214  DeclSpec &DS, unsigned AttrReqs, bool AtomicAllowed,
6215  bool IdentifierRequired,
6216  std::optional<llvm::function_ref<void()>> CodeCompletionHandler) {
6217  if ((AttrReqs & AR_CXX11AttributesParsed) &&
6218  isAllowedCXX11AttributeSpecifier()) {
6219  ParsedAttributes Attrs(AttrFactory);
6220  ParseCXX11Attributes(Attrs);
6221  DS.takeAttributesFrom(Attrs);
6222  }
6223 
6224  SourceLocation EndLoc;
6225 
6226  while (true) {
6227  bool isInvalid = false;
6228  const char *PrevSpec = nullptr;
6229  unsigned DiagID = 0;
6230  SourceLocation Loc = Tok.getLocation();
6231 
6232  switch (Tok.getKind()) {
6233  case tok::code_completion:
6234  cutOffParsing();
6235  if (CodeCompletionHandler)
6236  (*CodeCompletionHandler)();
6237  else
6238  Actions.CodeCompleteTypeQualifiers(DS);
6239  return;
6240 
6241  case tok::kw_const:
6242  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeQual(DeclSpec::TQ_const , Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID,
6243  getLangOpts());
6244  break;
6245  case tok::kw_volatile:
6246  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeQual(DeclSpec::TQ_volatile, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID,
6247  getLangOpts());
6248  break;
6249  case tok::kw_restrict:
6250  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeQual(DeclSpec::TQ_restrict, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID,
6251  getLangOpts());
6252  break;
6253  case tok::kw__Atomic:
6254  if (!AtomicAllowed)
6255  goto DoneWithTypeQuals;
6256  diagnoseUseOfC11Keyword(Tok);
6257  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeQual(DeclSpec::TQ_atomic, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID,
6258  getLangOpts());
6259  break;
6260 
6261  // OpenCL qualifiers:
6262  case tok::kw_private:
6263  if (!getLangOpts().OpenCL)
6264  goto DoneWithTypeQuals;
6265  [[fallthrough]];
6266  case tok::kw___private:
6267  case tok::kw___global:
6268  case tok::kw___local:
6269  case tok::kw___constant:
6270  case tok::kw___generic:
6271  case tok::kw___read_only:
6272  case tok::kw___write_only:
6273  case tok::kw___read_write:
6274  ParseOpenCLQualifiers(DS.getAttributes());
6275  break;
6276 
6277  case tok::kw_groupshared:
6278  case tok::kw_in:
6279  case tok::kw_inout:
6280  case tok::kw_out:
6281  // NOTE: ParseHLSLQualifiers will consume the qualifier token.
6282  ParseHLSLQualifiers(DS.getAttributes());
6283  continue;
6284 
6285  case tok::kw___unaligned:
6286  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeQual(DeclSpec::TQ_unaligned, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID,
6287  getLangOpts());
6288  break;
6289  case tok::kw___uptr:
6290  // GNU libc headers in C mode use '__uptr' as an identifier which conflicts
6291  // with the MS modifier keyword.
6292  if ((AttrReqs & AR_DeclspecAttributesParsed) && !getLangOpts().CPlusPlus &&
6293  IdentifierRequired && DS.isEmpty() && NextToken().is(tok::semi)) {
6294  if (TryKeywordIdentFallback(false))
6295  continue;
6296  }
6297  [[fallthrough]];
6298  case tok::kw___sptr:
6299  case tok::kw___w64:
6300  case tok::kw___ptr64:
6301  case tok::kw___ptr32:
6302  case tok::kw___cdecl:
6303  case tok::kw___stdcall:
6304  case tok::kw___fastcall:
6305  case tok::kw___thiscall:
6306  case tok::kw___regcall:
6307  case tok::kw___vectorcall:
6308  if (AttrReqs & AR_DeclspecAttributesParsed) {
6309  ParseMicrosoftTypeAttributes(DS.getAttributes());
6310  continue;
6311  }
6312  goto DoneWithTypeQuals;
6313 
6314  case tok::kw___funcref:
6315  ParseWebAssemblyFuncrefTypeAttribute(DS.getAttributes());
6316  continue;
6317  goto DoneWithTypeQuals;
6318 
6319  case tok::kw___pascal:
6320  if (AttrReqs & AR_VendorAttributesParsed) {
6321  ParseBorlandTypeAttributes(DS.getAttributes());
6322  continue;
6323  }
6324  goto DoneWithTypeQuals;
6325 
6326  // Nullability type specifiers.
6327  case tok::kw__Nonnull:
6328  case tok::kw__Nullable:
6329  case tok::kw__Nullable_result:
6330  case tok::kw__Null_unspecified:
6331  ParseNullabilityTypeSpecifiers(DS.getAttributes());
6332  continue;
6333 
6334  // Objective-C 'kindof' types.
6335  case tok::kw___kindof:
6336  DS.getAttributes().addNew(Tok.getIdentifierInfo(), Loc, nullptr, Loc,
6337  nullptr, 0, tok::kw___kindof);
6338  (void)ConsumeToken();
6339  continue;
6340 
6341  case tok::kw___attribute:
6342  if (AttrReqs & AR_GNUAttributesParsedAndRejected)
6343  // When GNU attributes are expressly forbidden, diagnose their usage.
6344  Diag(Tok, diag::err_attributes_not_allowed);
6345 
6346  // Parse the attributes even if they are rejected to ensure that error
6347  // recovery is graceful.
6348  if (AttrReqs & AR_GNUAttributesParsed ||
6349  AttrReqs & AR_GNUAttributesParsedAndRejected) {
6350  ParseGNUAttributes(DS.getAttributes());
6351  continue; // do *not* consume the next token!
6352  }
6353  // otherwise, FALL THROUGH!
6354  [[fallthrough]];
6355  default:
6356  DoneWithTypeQuals:
6357  // If this is not a type-qualifier token, we're done reading type
6358  // qualifiers. First verify that DeclSpec's are consistent.
6359  DS.Finish(Actions, Actions.getASTContext().getPrintingPolicy());
6360  if (EndLoc.isValid())
6361  DS.SetRangeEnd(EndLoc);
6362  return;
6363  }
6364 
6365  // If the specifier combination wasn't legal, issue a diagnostic.
6366  if (isInvalid) {
6367  assert(PrevSpec && "Method did not return previous specifier!");
6368  Diag(Tok, DiagID) << PrevSpec;
6369  }
6370  EndLoc = ConsumeToken();
6371  }
6372 }
6373 
6374 /// ParseDeclarator - Parse and verify a newly-initialized declarator.
6375 void Parser::ParseDeclarator(Declarator &D) {
6376  /// This implements the 'declarator' production in the C grammar, then checks
6377  /// for well-formedness and issues diagnostics.
6378  Actions.runWithSufficientStackSpace(D.getBeginLoc(), [&] {
6379  ParseDeclaratorInternal(D, &Parser::ParseDirectDeclarator);
6380  });
6381 }
6382 
6383 static bool isPtrOperatorToken(tok::TokenKind Kind, const LangOptions &Lang,
6384  DeclaratorContext TheContext) {
6385  if (Kind == tok::star || Kind == tok::caret)
6386  return true;
6387 
6388  // OpenCL 2.0 and later define this keyword.
6389  if (Kind == tok::kw_pipe && Lang.OpenCL &&
6390  Lang.getOpenCLCompatibleVersion() >= 200)
6391  return true;
6392 
6393  if (!Lang.CPlusPlus)
6394  return false;
6395 
6396  if (Kind == tok::amp)
6397  return true;
6398 
6399  // We parse rvalue refs in C++03, because otherwise the errors are scary.
6400  // But we must not parse them in conversion-type-ids and new-type-ids, since
6401  // those can be legitimately followed by a && operator.
6402  // (The same thing can in theory happen after a trailing-return-type, but
6403  // since those are a C++11 feature, there is no rejects-valid issue there.)
6404  if (Kind == tok::ampamp)
6405  return Lang.CPlusPlus11 || (TheContext != DeclaratorContext::ConversionId &&
6406  TheContext != DeclaratorContext::CXXNew);
6407 
6408  return false;
6409 }
6410 
6411 // Indicates whether the given declarator is a pipe declarator.
6412 static bool isPipeDeclarator(const Declarator &D) {
6413  const unsigned NumTypes = D.getNumTypeObjects();
6414 
6415  for (unsigned Idx = 0; Idx != NumTypes; ++Idx)
6416  if (DeclaratorChunk::Pipe == D.getTypeObject(Idx).Kind)
6417  return true;
6418 
6419  return false;
6420 }
6421 
6422 /// ParseDeclaratorInternal - Parse a C or C++ declarator. The direct-declarator
6423 /// is parsed by the function passed to it. Pass null, and the direct-declarator
6424 /// isn't parsed at all, making this function effectively parse the C++
6425 /// ptr-operator production.
6426 ///
6427 /// If the grammar of this construct is extended, matching changes must also be
6428 /// made to TryParseDeclarator and MightBeDeclarator, and possibly to
6429 /// isConstructorDeclarator.
6430 ///
6431 /// declarator: [C99 6.7.5] [C++ 8p4, dcl.decl]
6432 /// [C] pointer[opt] direct-declarator
6433 /// [C++] direct-declarator
6434 /// [C++] ptr-operator declarator
6435 ///
6436 /// pointer: [C99 6.7.5]
6437 /// '*' type-qualifier-list[opt]
6438 /// '*' type-qualifier-list[opt] pointer
6439 ///
6440 /// ptr-operator:
6441 /// '*' cv-qualifier-seq[opt]
6442 /// '&'
6443 /// [C++0x] '&&'
6444 /// [GNU] '&' restrict[opt] attributes[opt]
6445 /// [GNU?] '&&' restrict[opt] attributes[opt]
6446 /// '::'[opt] nested-name-specifier '*' cv-qualifier-seq[opt]
6447 void Parser::ParseDeclaratorInternal(Declarator &D,
6448  DirectDeclParseFunction DirectDeclParser) {
6449  if (Diags.hasAllExtensionsSilenced())
6450  D.setExtension();
6451 
6452  // C++ member pointers start with a '::' or a nested-name.
6453  // Member pointers get special handling, since there's no place for the
6454  // scope spec in the generic path below.
6455  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus &&
6456  (Tok.is(tok::coloncolon) || Tok.is(tok::kw_decltype) ||
6457  (Tok.is(tok::identifier) &&
6458  (NextToken().is(tok::coloncolon) || NextToken().is(tok::less))) ||
6459  Tok.is(tok::annot_cxxscope))) {
6460  bool EnteringContext = D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::File ||
6461  D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member;
6462  CXXScopeSpec SS;
6463  SS.setTemplateParamLists(D.getTemplateParameterLists());
6464  ParseOptionalCXXScopeSpecifier(SS, /*ObjectType=*/nullptr,
6465  /*ObjectHasErrors=*/false, EnteringContext);
6466 
6467  if (SS.isNotEmpty()) {
6468  if (Tok.isNot(tok::star)) {
6469  // The scope spec really belongs to the direct-declarator.
6470  if (D.mayHaveIdentifier())
6471  D.getCXXScopeSpec() = SS;
6472  else
6473  AnnotateScopeToken(SS, true);
6474 
6475  if (DirectDeclParser)
6476  (this->*DirectDeclParser)(D);
6477  return;
6478  }
6479 
6480  if (SS.isValid()) {
6481  checkCompoundToken(SS.getEndLoc(), tok::coloncolon,
6482  CompoundToken::MemberPtr);
6483  }
6484 
6485  SourceLocation StarLoc = ConsumeToken();
6486  D.SetRangeEnd(StarLoc);
6487  DeclSpec DS(AttrFactory);
6488  ParseTypeQualifierListOpt(DS);
6489  D.ExtendWithDeclSpec(DS);
6490 
6491  // Recurse to parse whatever is left.
6492  Actions.runWithSufficientStackSpace(D.getBeginLoc(), [&] {
6493  ParseDeclaratorInternal(D, DirectDeclParser);
6494  });
6495 
6496  // Sema will have to catch (syntactically invalid) pointers into global
6497  // scope. It has to catch pointers into namespace scope anyway.
6498  D.AddTypeInfo(DeclaratorChunk::getMemberPointer(
6499  SS, DS.getTypeQualifiers(), StarLoc, DS.getEndLoc()),
6500  std::move(DS.getAttributes()),
6501  /* Don't replace range end. */ SourceLocation());
6502  return;
6503  }
6504  }
6505 
6506  tok::TokenKind Kind = Tok.getKind();
6507 
6508  if (D.getDeclSpec().isTypeSpecPipe() && !isPipeDeclarator(D)) {
6509  DeclSpec DS(AttrFactory);
6510  ParseTypeQualifierListOpt(DS);
6511 
6512  D.AddTypeInfo(
6513  DeclaratorChunk::getPipe(DS.getTypeQualifiers(), DS.getPipeLoc()),
6514  std::move(DS.getAttributes()), SourceLocation());
6515  }
6516 
6517  // Not a pointer, C++ reference, or block.
6518  if (!isPtrOperatorToken(Kind, getLangOpts(), D.getContext())) {
6519  if (DirectDeclParser)
6520  (this->*DirectDeclParser)(D);
6521  return;
6522  }
6523 
6524  // Otherwise, '*' -> pointer, '^' -> block, '&' -> lvalue reference,
6525  // '&&' -> rvalue reference
6526  SourceLocation Loc = ConsumeToken(); // Eat the *, ^, & or &&.
6527  D.SetRangeEnd(Loc);
6528 
6529  if (Kind == tok::star || Kind == tok::caret) {
6530  // Is a pointer.
6531  DeclSpec DS(AttrFactory);
6532 
6533  // GNU attributes are not allowed here in a new-type-id, but Declspec and
6534  // C++11 attributes are allowed.
6535  unsigned Reqs = AR_CXX11AttributesParsed | AR_DeclspecAttributesParsed |
6536  ((D.getContext() != DeclaratorContext::CXXNew)
6537  ? AR_GNUAttributesParsed
6538  : AR_GNUAttributesParsedAndRejected);
6539  ParseTypeQualifierListOpt(DS, Reqs, true, !D.mayOmitIdentifier());
6540  D.ExtendWithDeclSpec(DS);
6541 
6542  // Recursively parse the declarator.
6543  Actions.runWithSufficientStackSpace(
6544  D.getBeginLoc(), [&] { ParseDeclaratorInternal(D, DirectDeclParser); });
6545  if (Kind == tok::star)
6546  // Remember that we parsed a pointer type, and remember the type-quals.
6547  D.AddTypeInfo(DeclaratorChunk::getPointer(
6548  DS.getTypeQualifiers(), Loc, DS.getConstSpecLoc(),
6549  DS.getVolatileSpecLoc(), DS.getRestrictSpecLoc(),
6550  DS.getAtomicSpecLoc(), DS.getUnalignedSpecLoc()),
6551  std::move(DS.getAttributes()), SourceLocation());
6552  else
6553  // Remember that we parsed a Block type, and remember the type-quals.
6554  D.AddTypeInfo(
6555  DeclaratorChunk::getBlockPointer(DS.getTypeQualifiers(), Loc),
6556  std::move(DS.getAttributes()), SourceLocation());
6557  } else {
6558  // Is a reference
6559  DeclSpec DS(AttrFactory);
6560 
6561  // Complain about rvalue references in C++03, but then go on and build
6562  // the declarator.
6563  if (Kind == tok::ampamp)
6564  Diag(Loc, getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 ?
6565  diag::warn_cxx98_compat_rvalue_reference :
6566  diag::ext_rvalue_reference);
6567 
6568  // GNU-style and C++11 attributes are allowed here, as is restrict.
6569  ParseTypeQualifierListOpt(DS);
6570  D.ExtendWithDeclSpec(DS);
6571 
6572  // C++ 8.3.2p1: cv-qualified references are ill-formed except when the
6573  // cv-qualifiers are introduced through the use of a typedef or of a
6574  // template type argument, in which case the cv-qualifiers are ignored.
6575  if (DS.getTypeQualifiers() != DeclSpec::TQ_unspecified) {
6576  if (DS.getTypeQualifiers() & DeclSpec::TQ_const)
6577  Diag(DS.getConstSpecLoc(),
6578  diag::err_invalid_reference_qualifier_application) << "const";
6579  if (DS.getTypeQualifiers() & DeclSpec::TQ_volatile)
6580  Diag(DS.getVolatileSpecLoc(),
6581  diag::err_invalid_reference_qualifier_application) << "volatile";
6582  // 'restrict' is permitted as an extension.
6583  if (DS.getTypeQualifiers() & DeclSpec::TQ_atomic)
6584  Diag(DS.getAtomicSpecLoc(),
6585  diag::err_invalid_reference_qualifier_application) << "_Atomic";
6586  }
6587 
6588  // Recursively parse the declarator.
6589  Actions.runWithSufficientStackSpace(
6590  D.getBeginLoc(), [&] { ParseDeclaratorInternal(D, DirectDeclParser); });
6591 
6592  if (D.getNumTypeObjects() > 0) {
6593  // C++ [dcl.ref]p4: There shall be no references to references.
6594  DeclaratorChunk& InnerChunk = D.getTypeObject(D.getNumTypeObjects() - 1);
6595  if (InnerChunk.Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Reference) {
6596  if (const IdentifierInfo *II = D.getIdentifier())
6597  Diag(InnerChunk.Loc, diag::err_illegal_decl_reference_to_reference)
6598  << II;
6599  else
6600  Diag(InnerChunk.Loc, diag::err_illegal_decl_reference_to_reference)
6601  << "type name";
6602 
6603  // Once we've complained about the reference-to-reference, we
6604  // can go ahead and build the (technically ill-formed)
6605  // declarator: reference collapsing will take care of it.
6606  }
6607  }
6608 
6609  // Remember that we parsed a reference type.
6610  D.AddTypeInfo(DeclaratorChunk::getReference(DS.getTypeQualifiers(), Loc,
6611  Kind == tok::amp),
6612  std::move(DS.getAttributes()), SourceLocation());
6613  }
6614 }
6615 
6616 // When correcting from misplaced brackets before the identifier, the location
6617 // is saved inside the declarator so that other diagnostic messages can use
6618 // them. This extracts and returns that location, or returns the provided
6619 // location if a stored location does not exist.
6620 static SourceLocation getMissingDeclaratorIdLoc(Declarator &D,
6621  SourceLocation Loc) {
6622  if (D.getName().StartLocation.isInvalid() &&
6623  D.getName().EndLocation.isValid())
6624  return D.getName().EndLocation;
6625 
6626  return Loc;
6627 }
6628 
6629 /// ParseDirectDeclarator
6630 /// direct-declarator: [C99 6.7.5]
6631 /// [C99] identifier
6632 /// '(' declarator ')'
6633 /// [GNU] '(' attributes declarator ')'
6634 /// [C90] direct-declarator '[' constant-expression[opt] ']'
6635 /// [C99] direct-declarator '[' type-qual-list[opt] assignment-expr[opt] ']'
6636 /// [C99] direct-declarator '[' 'static' type-qual-list[opt] assign-expr ']'
6637 /// [C99] direct-declarator '[' type-qual-list 'static' assignment-expr ']'
6638 /// [C99] direct-declarator '[' type-qual-list[opt] '*' ']'
6639 /// [C++11] direct-declarator '[' constant-expression[opt] ']'
6640 /// attribute-specifier-seq[opt]
6641 /// direct-declarator '(' parameter-type-list ')'
6642 /// direct-declarator '(' identifier-list[opt] ')'
6643 /// [GNU] direct-declarator '(' parameter-forward-declarations
6644 /// parameter-type-list[opt] ')'
6645 /// [C++] direct-declarator '(' parameter-declaration-clause ')'
6646 /// cv-qualifier-seq[opt] exception-specification[opt]
6647 /// [C++11] direct-declarator '(' parameter-declaration-clause ')'
6648 /// attribute-specifier-seq[opt] cv-qualifier-seq[opt]
6649 /// ref-qualifier[opt] exception-specification[opt]
6650 /// [C++] declarator-id
6651 /// [C++11] declarator-id attribute-specifier-seq[opt]
6652 ///
6653 /// declarator-id: [C++ 8]
6654 /// '...'[opt] id-expression
6655 /// '::'[opt] nested-name-specifier[opt] type-name
6656 ///
6657 /// id-expression: [C++ 5.1]
6658 /// unqualified-id
6659 /// qualified-id
6660 ///
6661 /// unqualified-id: [C++ 5.1]
6662 /// identifier
6663 /// operator-function-id
6664 /// conversion-function-id
6665 /// '~' class-name
6666 /// template-id
6667 ///
6668 /// C++17 adds the following, which we also handle here:
6669 ///
6670 /// simple-declaration:
6671 /// <decl-spec> '[' identifier-list ']' brace-or-equal-initializer ';'
6672 ///
6673 /// Note, any additional constructs added here may need corresponding changes
6674 /// in isConstructorDeclarator.
6675 void Parser::ParseDirectDeclarator(Declarator &D) {
6676  DeclaratorScopeObj DeclScopeObj(*this, D.getCXXScopeSpec());
6677 
6678  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus && D.mayHaveIdentifier()) {
6679  // This might be a C++17 structured binding.
6680  if (Tok.is(tok::l_square) && !D.mayOmitIdentifier() &&
6681  D.getCXXScopeSpec().isEmpty())
6682  return ParseDecompositionDeclarator(D);
6683 
6684  // Don't parse FOO:BAR as if it were a typo for FOO::BAR inside a class, in
6685  // this context it is a bitfield. Also in range-based for statement colon
6686  // may delimit for-range-declaration.
6687  ColonProtectionRAIIObject X(
6688  *this, D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member ||
6689  (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::ForInit &&
6690  getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11));
6691 
6692  // ParseDeclaratorInternal might already have parsed the scope.
6693  if (D.getCXXScopeSpec().isEmpty()) {
6694  bool EnteringContext = D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::File ||
6695  D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member;
6696  ParseOptionalCXXScopeSpecifier(
6697  D.getCXXScopeSpec(), /*ObjectType=*/nullptr,
6698  /*ObjectHasErrors=*/false, EnteringContext);
6699  }
6700 
6701  // C++23 [basic.scope.namespace]p1:
6702  // For each non-friend redeclaration or specialization whose target scope
6703  // is or is contained by the scope, the portion after the declarator-id,
6704  // class-head-name, or enum-head-name is also included in the scope.
6705  // C++23 [basic.scope.class]p1:
6706  // For each non-friend redeclaration or specialization whose target scope
6707  // is or is contained by the scope, the portion after the declarator-id,
6708  // class-head-name, or enum-head-name is also included in the scope.
6709  //
6710  // FIXME: We should not be doing this for friend declarations; they have
6711  // their own special lookup semantics specified by [basic.lookup.unqual]p6.
6712  if (D.getCXXScopeSpec().isValid()) {
6713  if (Actions.ShouldEnterDeclaratorScope(getCurScope(),
6714  D.getCXXScopeSpec()))
6715  // Change the declaration context for name lookup, until this function
6716  // is exited (and the declarator has been parsed).
6717  DeclScopeObj.EnterDeclaratorScope();
6718  else if (getObjCDeclContext()) {
6719  // Ensure that we don't interpret the next token as an identifier when
6720  // dealing with declarations in an Objective-C container.
6721  D.SetIdentifier(nullptr, Tok.getLocation());
6722  D.setInvalidType(true);
6723  ConsumeToken();
6724  goto PastIdentifier;
6725  }
6726  }
6727 
6728  // C++0x [dcl.fct]p14:
6729  // There is a syntactic ambiguity when an ellipsis occurs at the end of a
6730  // parameter-declaration-clause without a preceding comma. In this case,
6731  // the ellipsis is parsed as part of the abstract-declarator if the type
6732  // of the parameter either names a template parameter pack that has not
6733  // been expanded or contains auto; otherwise, it is parsed as part of the
6734  // parameter-declaration-clause.
6735  if (Tok.is(tok::ellipsis) && D.getCXXScopeSpec().isEmpty() &&
6736  !((D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Prototype ||
6737  D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::LambdaExprParameter ||
6738  D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::BlockLiteral) &&
6739  NextToken().is(tok::r_paren) && !D.hasGroupingParens() &&
6740  !Actions.containsUnexpandedParameterPacks(D) &&
6741  D.getDeclSpec().getTypeSpecType() != TST_auto)) {
6742  SourceLocation EllipsisLoc = ConsumeToken();
6743  if (isPtrOperatorToken(Tok.getKind(), getLangOpts(), D.getContext())) {
6744  // The ellipsis was put in the wrong place. Recover, and explain to
6745  // the user what they should have done.
6746  ParseDeclarator(D);
6747  if (EllipsisLoc.isValid())
6748  DiagnoseMisplacedEllipsisInDeclarator(EllipsisLoc, D);
6749  return;
6750  } else
6751  D.setEllipsisLoc(EllipsisLoc);
6752 
6753  // The ellipsis can't be followed by a parenthesized declarator. We
6754  // check for that in ParseParenDeclarator, after we have disambiguated
6755  // the l_paren token.
6756  }
6757 
6758  if (Tok.isOneOf(tok::identifier, tok::kw_operator, tok::annot_template_id,
6759  tok::tilde)) {
6760  // We found something that indicates the start of an unqualified-id.
6761  // Parse that unqualified-id.
6762  bool AllowConstructorName;
6763  bool AllowDeductionGuide;
6764  if (D.getDeclSpec().hasTypeSpecifier()) {
6765  AllowConstructorName = false;
6766  AllowDeductionGuide = false;
6767  } else if (D.getCXXScopeSpec().isSet()) {
6768  AllowConstructorName = (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::File ||
6769  D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member);
6770  AllowDeductionGuide = false;
6771  } else {
6772  AllowConstructorName = (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member);
6773  AllowDeductionGuide = (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::File ||
6774  D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member);
6775  }
6776 
6777  bool HadScope = D.getCXXScopeSpec().isValid();
6778  SourceLocation TemplateKWLoc;
6779  if (ParseUnqualifiedId(D.getCXXScopeSpec(),
6780  /*ObjectType=*/nullptr,
6781  /*ObjectHadErrors=*/false,
6782  /*EnteringContext=*/true,
6783  /*AllowDestructorName=*/true, AllowConstructorName,
6784  AllowDeductionGuide, &TemplateKWLoc,
6785  D.getName()) ||
6786  // Once we're past the identifier, if the scope was bad, mark the
6787  // whole declarator bad.
6788  D.getCXXScopeSpec().isInvalid()) {
6789  D.SetIdentifier(nullptr, Tok.getLocation());
6790  D.setInvalidType(true);
6791  } else {
6792  // ParseUnqualifiedId might have parsed a scope specifier during error
6793  // recovery. If it did so, enter that scope.
6794  if (!HadScope && D.getCXXScopeSpec().isValid() &&
6795  Actions.ShouldEnterDeclaratorScope(getCurScope(),
6796  D.getCXXScopeSpec()))
6797  DeclScopeObj.EnterDeclaratorScope();
6798 
6799  // Parsed the unqualified-id; update range information and move along.
6800  if (D.getSourceRange().getBegin().isInvalid())
6801  D.SetRangeBegin(D.getName().getSourceRange().getBegin());
6802  D.SetRangeEnd(D.getName().getSourceRange().getEnd());
6803  }
6804  goto PastIdentifier;
6805  }
6806 
6807  if (D.getCXXScopeSpec().isNotEmpty()) {
6808  // We have a scope specifier but no following unqualified-id.
6809  Diag(PP.getLocForEndOfToken(D.getCXXScopeSpec().getEndLoc()),
6810  diag::err_expected_unqualified_id)
6811  << /*C++*/1;
6812  D.SetIdentifier(nullptr, Tok.getLocation());
6813  goto PastIdentifier;
6814  }
6815  } else if (Tok.is(tok::identifier) && D.mayHaveIdentifier()) {
6816  assert(!getLangOpts().CPlusPlus &&
6817  "There's a C++-specific check for tok::identifier above");
6818  assert(Tok.getIdentifierInfo() && "Not an identifier?");
6819  D.SetIdentifier(Tok.getIdentifierInfo(), Tok.getLocation());
6820  D.SetRangeEnd(Tok.getLocation());
6821  ConsumeToken();
6822  goto PastIdentifier;
6823  } else if (Tok.is(tok::identifier) && !D.mayHaveIdentifier()) {
6824  // We're not allowed an identifier here, but we got one. Try to figure out
6825  // if the user was trying to attach a name to the type, or whether the name
6826  // is some unrelated trailing syntax.
6827  bool DiagnoseIdentifier = false;
6828  if (D.hasGroupingParens())
6829  // An identifier within parens is unlikely to be intended to be anything
6830  // other than a name being "declared".
6831  DiagnoseIdentifier = true;
6832  else if (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::TemplateArg)
6833  // T<int N> is an accidental identifier; T<int N indicates a missing '>'.
6834  DiagnoseIdentifier =
6835  NextToken().isOneOf(tok::comma, tok::greater, tok::greatergreater);
6836  else if (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::AliasDecl ||
6837  D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::AliasTemplate)
6838  // The most likely error is that the ';' was forgotten.
6839  DiagnoseIdentifier = NextToken().isOneOf(tok::comma, tok::semi);
6840  else if ((D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::TrailingReturn ||
6841  D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::TrailingReturnVar) &&
6842  !isCXX11VirtSpecifier(Tok))
6843  DiagnoseIdentifier = NextToken().isOneOf(
6844  tok::comma, tok::semi, tok::equal, tok::l_brace, tok::kw_try);
6845  if (DiagnoseIdentifier) {
6846  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), diag::err_unexpected_unqualified_id)
6847  << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(Tok.getLocation());
6848  D.SetIdentifier(nullptr, Tok.getLocation());
6849  ConsumeToken();
6850  goto PastIdentifier;
6851  }
6852  }
6853 
6854  if (Tok.is(tok::l_paren)) {
6855  // If this might be an abstract-declarator followed by a direct-initializer,
6856  // check whether this is a valid declarator chunk. If it can't be, assume
6857  // that it's an initializer instead.
6858  if (D.mayOmitIdentifier() && D.mayBeFollowedByCXXDirectInit()) {
6859  RevertingTentativeParsingAction PA(*this);
6860  if (TryParseDeclarator(true, D.mayHaveIdentifier(), true,
6861  D.getDeclSpec().getTypeSpecType() == TST_auto) ==
6862  TPResult::False) {
6863  D.SetIdentifier(nullptr, Tok.getLocation());
6864  goto PastIdentifier;
6865  }
6866  }
6867 
6868  // direct-declarator: '(' declarator ')'
6869  // direct-declarator: '(' attributes declarator ')'
6870  // Example: 'char (*X)' or 'int (*XX)(void)'
6871  ParseParenDeclarator(D);
6872 
6873  // If the declarator was parenthesized, we entered the declarator
6874  // scope when parsing the parenthesized declarator, then exited
6875  // the scope already. Re-enter the scope, if we need to.
6876  if (D.getCXXScopeSpec().isSet()) {
6877  // If there was an error parsing parenthesized declarator, declarator
6878  // scope may have been entered before. Don't do it again.
6879  if (!D.isInvalidType() &&
6880  Actions.ShouldEnterDeclaratorScope(getCurScope(),
6881  D.getCXXScopeSpec()))
6882  // Change the declaration context for name lookup, until this function
6883  // is exited (and the declarator has been parsed).
6884  DeclScopeObj.EnterDeclaratorScope();
6885  }
6886  } else if (D.mayOmitIdentifier()) {
6887  // This could be something simple like "int" (in which case the declarator
6888  // portion is empty), if an abstract-declarator is allowed.
6889  D.SetIdentifier(nullptr, Tok.getLocation());
6890 
6891  // The grammar for abstract-pack-declarator does not allow grouping parens.
6892  // FIXME: Revisit this once core issue 1488 is resolved.
6893  if (D.hasEllipsis() && D.hasGroupingParens())
6894  Diag(PP.getLocForEndOfToken(D.getEllipsisLoc()),
6895  diag::ext_abstract_pack_declarator_parens);
6896  } else {
6897  if (Tok.getKind() == tok::annot_pragma_parser_crash)
6898  LLVM_BUILTIN_TRAP;
6899  if (Tok.is(tok::l_square))
6900  return ParseMisplacedBracketDeclarator(D);
6901  if (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member) {
6902  // Objective-C++: Detect C++ keywords and try to prevent further errors by
6903  // treating these keyword as valid member names.
6904  if (getLangOpts().ObjC && getLangOpts().CPlusPlus &&
6905  !Tok.isAnnotation() && Tok.getIdentifierInfo() &&
6906  Tok.getIdentifierInfo()->isCPlusPlusKeyword(getLangOpts())) {
6907  Diag(getMissingDeclaratorIdLoc(D, Tok.getLocation()),
6908  diag::err_expected_member_name_or_semi_objcxx_keyword)
6909  << Tok.getIdentifierInfo()
6910  << (D.getDeclSpec().isEmpty() ? SourceRange()
6911  : D.getDeclSpec().getSourceRange());
6912  D.SetIdentifier(Tok.getIdentifierInfo(), Tok.getLocation());
6913  D.SetRangeEnd(Tok.getLocation());
6914  ConsumeToken();
6915  goto PastIdentifier;
6916  }
6917  Diag(getMissingDeclaratorIdLoc(D, Tok.getLocation()),
6918  diag::err_expected_member_name_or_semi)
6919  << (D.getDeclSpec().isEmpty() ? SourceRange()
6920  : D.getDeclSpec().getSourceRange());
6921  } else {
6922  if (Tok.getKind() == tok::TokenKind::kw_while) {
6923  Diag(Tok, diag::err_while_loop_outside_of_a_function);
6924  } else if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus) {
6925  if (Tok.isOneOf(tok::period, tok::arrow))
6926  Diag(Tok, diag::err_invalid_operator_on_type) << Tok.is(tok::arrow);
6927  else {
6928  SourceLocation Loc = D.getCXXScopeSpec().getEndLoc();
6929  if (Tok.isAtStartOfLine() && Loc.isValid())
6930  Diag(PP.getLocForEndOfToken(Loc), diag::err_expected_unqualified_id)
6931  << getLangOpts().CPlusPlus;
6932  else
6933  Diag(getMissingDeclaratorIdLoc(D, Tok.getLocation()),
6934  diag::err_expected_unqualified_id)
6935  << getLangOpts().CPlusPlus;
6936  }
6937  } else {
6938  Diag(getMissingDeclaratorIdLoc(D, Tok.getLocation()),
6939  diag::err_expected_either)
6940  << tok::identifier << tok::l_paren;
6941  }
6942  }
6943  D.SetIdentifier(nullptr, Tok.getLocation());
6944  D.setInvalidType(true);
6945  }
6946 
6947  PastIdentifier:
6948  assert(D.isPastIdentifier() &&
6949  "Haven't past the location of the identifier yet?");
6950 
6951  // Don't parse attributes unless we have parsed an unparenthesized name.
6952  if (D.hasName() && !D.getNumTypeObjects())
6953  MaybeParseCXX11Attributes(D);
6954 
6955  while (true) {
6956  if (Tok.is(tok::l_paren)) {
6957  bool IsFunctionDeclaration = D.isFunctionDeclaratorAFunctionDeclaration();
6958  // Enter function-declaration scope, limiting any declarators to the
6959  // function prototype scope, including parameter declarators.
6960  ParseScope PrototypeScope(this,
6961  Scope::FunctionPrototypeScope|Scope::DeclScope|
6962  (IsFunctionDeclaration
6963  ? Scope::FunctionDeclarationScope : 0));
6964 
6965  // The paren may be part of a C++ direct initializer, eg. "int x(1);".
6966  // In such a case, check if we actually have a function declarator; if it
6967  // is not, the declarator has been fully parsed.
6968  bool IsAmbiguous = false;
6969  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus && D.mayBeFollowedByCXXDirectInit()) {
6970  // C++2a [temp.res]p5
6971  // A qualified-id is assumed to name a type if
6972  // - [...]
6973  // - it is a decl-specifier of the decl-specifier-seq of a
6974  // - [...]
6975  // - parameter-declaration in a member-declaration [...]
6976  // - parameter-declaration in a declarator of a function or function
6977  // template declaration whose declarator-id is qualified [...]
6978  auto AllowImplicitTypename = ImplicitTypenameContext::No;
6979  if (D.getCXXScopeSpec().isSet())
6980  AllowImplicitTypename =
6981  (ImplicitTypenameContext)Actions.isDeclaratorFunctionLike(D);
6982  else if (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member) {
6983  AllowImplicitTypename = ImplicitTypenameContext::Yes;
6984  }
6985 
6986  // The name of the declarator, if any, is tentatively declared within
6987  // a possible direct initializer.
6988  TentativelyDeclaredIdentifiers.push_back(D.getIdentifier());
6989  bool IsFunctionDecl =
6990  isCXXFunctionDeclarator(&IsAmbiguous, AllowImplicitTypename);
6991  TentativelyDeclaredIdentifiers.pop_back();
6992  if (!IsFunctionDecl)
6993  break;
6994  }
6995  ParsedAttributes attrs(AttrFactory);
6996  BalancedDelimiterTracker T(*this, tok::l_paren);
6997  T.consumeOpen();
6998  if (IsFunctionDeclaration)
6999  Actions.ActOnStartFunctionDeclarationDeclarator(D,
7000  TemplateParameterDepth);
7001  ParseFunctionDeclarator(D, attrs, T, IsAmbiguous);
7002  if (IsFunctionDeclaration)
7003  Actions.ActOnFinishFunctionDeclarationDeclarator(D);
7004  PrototypeScope.Exit();
7005  } else if (Tok.is(tok::l_square)) {
7006  ParseBracketDeclarator(D);
7007  } else if (Tok.isRegularKeywordAttribute()) {
7008  // For consistency with attribute parsing.
7009  Diag(Tok, diag::err_keyword_not_allowed) << Tok.getIdentifierInfo();
7010  bool TakesArgs = doesKeywordAttributeTakeArgs(Tok.getKind());
7011  ConsumeToken();
7012  if (TakesArgs) {
7013  BalancedDelimiterTracker T(*this, tok::l_paren);
7014  if (!T.consumeOpen())
7015  T.skipToEnd();
7016  }
7017  } else if (Tok.is(tok::kw_requires) && D.hasGroupingParens()) {
7018  // This declarator is declaring a function, but the requires clause is
7019  // in the wrong place:
7020  // void (f() requires true);
7021  // instead of
7022  // void f() requires true;
7023  // or
7024  // void (f()) requires true;
7025  Diag(Tok, diag::err_requires_clause_inside_parens);
7026  ConsumeToken();
7027  ExprResult TrailingRequiresClause = Actions.CorrectDelayedTyposInExpr(
7028  ParseConstraintLogicalOrExpression(/*IsTrailingRequiresClause=*/true));
7029  if (TrailingRequiresClause.isUsable() && D.isFunctionDeclarator() &&
7030  !D.hasTrailingRequiresClause())
7031  // We're already ill-formed if we got here but we'll accept it anyway.
7032  D.setTrailingRequiresClause(TrailingRequiresClause.get());
7033  } else {
7034  break;
7035  }
7036  }
7037 }
7038 
7039 void Parser::ParseDecompositionDeclarator(Declarator &D) {
7040  assert(Tok.is(tok::l_square));
7041 
7042  // If this doesn't look like a structured binding, maybe it's a misplaced
7043  // array declarator.
7044  // FIXME: Consume the l_square first so we don't need extra lookahead for
7045  // this.
7046  if (!(NextToken().is(tok::identifier) &&
7047  GetLookAheadToken(2).isOneOf(tok::comma, tok::r_square)) &&
7048  !(NextToken().is(tok::r_square) &&
7049  GetLookAheadToken(2).isOneOf(tok::equal, tok::l_brace)))
7050  return ParseMisplacedBracketDeclarator(D);
7051 
7052  BalancedDelimiterTracker T(*this, tok::l_square);
7053  T.consumeOpen();
7054 
7055  SmallVector<DecompositionDeclarator::Binding, 32> Bindings;
7056  while (Tok.isNot(tok::r_square)) {
7057  if (!Bindings.empty()) {
7058  if (Tok.is(tok::comma))
7059  ConsumeToken();
7060  else {
7061  if (Tok.is(tok::identifier)) {
7062  SourceLocation EndLoc = getEndOfPreviousToken();
7063  Diag(EndLoc, diag::err_expected)
7064  << tok::comma << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(EndLoc, ",");
7065  } else {
7066  Diag(Tok, diag::err_expected_comma_or_rsquare);
7067  }
7068 
7069  SkipUntil(tok::r_square, tok::comma, tok::identifier,
7070  StopAtSemi | StopBeforeMatch);
7071  if (Tok.is(tok::comma))
7072  ConsumeToken();
7073  else if (Tok.isNot(tok::identifier))
7074  break;
7075  }
7076  }
7077 
7078  if (Tok.isNot(tok::identifier)) {
7079  Diag(Tok, diag::err_expected) << tok::identifier;
7080  break;
7081  }
7082 
7083  Bindings.push_back({Tok.getIdentifierInfo(), Tok.getLocation()});
7084  ConsumeToken();
7085  }
7086 
7087  if (Tok.isNot(tok::r_square))
7088  // We've already diagnosed a problem here.
7089  T.skipToEnd();
7090  else {
7091  // C++17 does not allow the identifier-list in a structured binding
7092  // to be empty.
7093  if (Bindings.empty())
7094  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), diag::ext_decomp_decl_empty);
7095 
7096  T.consumeClose();
7097  }
7098 
7099  return D.setDecompositionBindings(T.getOpenLocation(), Bindings,
7100  T.getCloseLocation());
7101 }
7102 
7103 /// ParseParenDeclarator - We parsed the declarator D up to a paren. This is
7104 /// only called before the identifier, so these are most likely just grouping
7105 /// parens for precedence. If we find that these are actually function
7106 /// parameter parens in an abstract-declarator, we call ParseFunctionDeclarator.
7107 ///
7108 /// direct-declarator:
7109 /// '(' declarator ')'
7110 /// [GNU] '(' attributes declarator ')'
7111 /// direct-declarator '(' parameter-type-list ')'
7112 /// direct-declarator '(' identifier-list[opt] ')'
7113 /// [GNU] direct-declarator '(' parameter-forward-declarations
7114 /// parameter-type-list[opt] ')'
7115 ///
7116 void Parser::ParseParenDeclarator(Declarator &D) {
7117  BalancedDelimiterTracker T(*this, tok::l_paren);
7118  T.consumeOpen();
7119 
7120  assert(!D.isPastIdentifier() && "Should be called before passing identifier");
7121 
7122  // Eat any attributes before we look at whether this is a grouping or function
7123  // declarator paren. If this is a grouping paren, the attribute applies to
7124  // the type being built up, for example:
7125  // int (__attribute__(()) *x)(long y)
7126  // If this ends up not being a grouping paren, the attribute applies to the
7127  // first argument, for example:
7128  // int (__attribute__(()) int x)
7129  // In either case, we need to eat any attributes to be able to determine what
7130  // sort of paren this is.
7131  //
7132  ParsedAttributes attrs(AttrFactory);
7133  bool RequiresArg = false;
7134  if (Tok.is(tok::kw___attribute)) {
7135  ParseGNUAttributes(attrs);
7136 
7137  // We require that the argument list (if this is a non-grouping paren) be
7138  // present even if the attribute list was empty.
7139  RequiresArg = true;
7140  }
7141 
7142  // Eat any Microsoft extensions.
7143  ParseMicrosoftTypeAttributes(attrs);
7144 
7145  // Eat any Borland extensions.
7146  if (Tok.is(tok::kw___pascal))
7147  ParseBorlandTypeAttributes(attrs);
7148 
7149  // If we haven't past the identifier yet (or where the identifier would be
7150  // stored, if this is an abstract declarator), then this is probably just
7151  // grouping parens. However, if this could be an abstract-declarator, then
7152  // this could also be the start of function arguments (consider 'void()').
7153  bool isGrouping;
7154 
7155  if (!D.mayOmitIdentifier()) {
7156  // If this can't be an abstract-declarator, this *must* be a grouping
7157  // paren, because we haven't seen the identifier yet.
7158  isGrouping = true;
7159  } else if (Tok.is(tok::r_paren) || // 'int()' is a function.
7160  (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus && Tok.is(tok::ellipsis) &&
7161  NextToken().is(tok::r_paren)) || // C++ int(...)
7162  isDeclarationSpecifier(
7163  ImplicitTypenameContext::No) || // 'int(int)' is a function.
7164  isCXX11AttributeSpecifier()) { // 'int([[]]int)' is a function.
7165  // This handles C99 6.7.5.3p11: in "typedef int X; void foo(X)", X is
7166  // considered to be a type, not a K&R identifier-list.
7167  isGrouping = false;
7168  } else {
7169  // Otherwise, this is a grouping paren, e.g. 'int (*X)' or 'int(X)'.
7170  isGrouping = true;
7171  }
7172 
7173  // If this is a grouping paren, handle:
7174  // direct-declarator: '(' declarator ')'
7175  // direct-declarator: '(' attributes declarator ')'
7176  if (isGrouping) {
7177  SourceLocation EllipsisLoc = D.getEllipsisLoc();
7178  D.setEllipsisLoc(SourceLocation());
7179 
7180  bool hadGroupingParens = D.hasGroupingParens();
7181  D.setGroupingParens(true);
7182  ParseDeclaratorInternal(D, &Parser::ParseDirectDeclarator);
7183  // Match the ')'.
7184  T.consumeClose();
7185  D.AddTypeInfo(
7186  DeclaratorChunk::getParen(T.getOpenLocation(), T.getCloseLocation()),
7187  std::move(attrs), T.getCloseLocation());
7188 
7189  D.setGroupingParens(hadGroupingParens);
7190 
7191  // An ellipsis cannot be placed outside parentheses.
7192  if (EllipsisLoc.isValid())
7193  DiagnoseMisplacedEllipsisInDeclarator(EllipsisLoc, D);
7194 
7195  return;
7196  }
7197 
7198  // Okay, if this wasn't a grouping paren, it must be the start of a function
7199  // argument list. Recognize that this declarator will never have an
7200  // identifier (and remember where it would have been), then call into
7201  // ParseFunctionDeclarator to handle of argument list.
7202  D.SetIdentifier(nullptr, Tok.getLocation());
7203 
7204  // Enter function-declaration scope, limiting any declarators to the
7205  // function prototype scope, including parameter declarators.
7206  ParseScope PrototypeScope(this,
7207  Scope::FunctionPrototypeScope | Scope::DeclScope |
7208  (D.isFunctionDeclaratorAFunctionDeclaration()
7209  ? Scope::FunctionDeclarationScope : 0));
7210  ParseFunctionDeclarator(D, attrs, T, false, RequiresArg);
7211  PrototypeScope.Exit();
7212 }
7213 
7214 void Parser::InitCXXThisScopeForDeclaratorIfRelevant(
7215  const Declarator &D, const DeclSpec &DS,
7216  std::optional<Sema::CXXThisScopeRAII> &ThisScope) {
7217  // C++11 [expr.prim.general]p3:
7218  // If a declaration declares a member function or member function
7219  // template of a class X, the expression this is a prvalue of type
7220  // "pointer to cv-qualifier-seq X" between the optional cv-qualifer-seq
7221  // and the end of the function-definition, member-declarator, or
7222  // declarator.
7223  // FIXME: currently, "static" case isn't handled correctly.
7224  bool IsCXX11MemberFunction =
7225  getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 &&
7226  D.getDeclSpec().getStorageClassSpec() != DeclSpec::SCS_typedef &&
7227  (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::Member
7228  ? !D.getDeclSpec().isFriendSpecified()
7229  : D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::File &&
7230  D.getCXXScopeSpec().isValid() &&
7231  Actions.CurContext->isRecord());
7232  if (!IsCXX11MemberFunction)
7233  return;
7234 
7235  Qualifiers Q = Qualifiers::fromCVRUMask(DS.getTypeQualifiers());
7236  if (D.getDeclSpec().hasConstexprSpecifier() && !getLangOpts().CPlusPlus14)
7237  Q.addConst();
7238  // FIXME: Collect C++ address spaces.
7239  // If there are multiple different address spaces, the source is invalid.
7240  // Carry on using the first addr space for the qualifiers of 'this'.
7241  // The diagnostic will be given later while creating the function
7242  // prototype for the method.
7243  if (getLangOpts().OpenCLCPlusPlus) {
7244  for (ParsedAttr &attr : DS.getAttributes()) {
7245  LangAS ASIdx = attr.asOpenCLLangAS();
7246  if (ASIdx != LangAS::Default) {
7247  Q.addAddressSpace(ASIdx);
7248  break;
7249  }
7250  }
7251  }
7252  ThisScope.emplace(Actions, dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Actions.CurContext), Q,
7253  IsCXX11MemberFunction);
7254 }
7255 
7256 /// ParseFunctionDeclarator - We are after the identifier and have parsed the
7257 /// declarator D up to a paren, which indicates that we are parsing function
7258 /// arguments.
7259 ///
7260 /// If FirstArgAttrs is non-null, then the caller parsed those attributes
7261 /// immediately after the open paren - they will be applied to the DeclSpec
7262 /// of the first parameter.
7263 ///
7264 /// If RequiresArg is true, then the first argument of the function is required
7265 /// to be present and required to not be an identifier list.
7266 ///
7267 /// For C++, after the parameter-list, it also parses the cv-qualifier-seq[opt],
7268 /// (C++11) ref-qualifier[opt], exception-specification[opt],
7269 /// (C++11) attribute-specifier-seq[opt], (C++11) trailing-return-type[opt] and
7270 /// (C++2a) the trailing requires-clause.
7271 ///
7272 /// [C++11] exception-specification:
7273 /// dynamic-exception-specification
7274 /// noexcept-specification
7275 ///
7276 void Parser::ParseFunctionDeclarator(Declarator &D,
7277  ParsedAttributes &FirstArgAttrs,
7278  BalancedDelimiterTracker &Tracker,
7279  bool IsAmbiguous,
7280  bool RequiresArg) {
7281  assert(getCurScope()->isFunctionPrototypeScope() &&
7282  "Should call from a Function scope");
7283  // lparen is already consumed!
7284  assert(D.isPastIdentifier() && "Should not call before identifier!");
7285 
7286  // This should be true when the function has typed arguments.
7287  // Otherwise, it is treated as a K&R-style function.
7288  bool HasProto = false;
7289  // Build up an array of information about the parsed arguments.
7290  SmallVector<DeclaratorChunk::ParamInfo, 16> ParamInfo;
7291  // Remember where we see an ellipsis, if any.
7292  SourceLocation EllipsisLoc;
7293 
7294  DeclSpec DS(AttrFactory);
7295  bool RefQualifierIsLValueRef = true;
7296  SourceLocation RefQualifierLoc;
7297  ExceptionSpecificationType ESpecType = EST_None;
7298  SourceRange ESpecRange;
7299  SmallVector<ParsedType, 2> DynamicExceptions;
7300  SmallVector<SourceRange, 2> DynamicExceptionRanges;
7301  ExprResult NoexceptExpr;
7302  CachedTokens *ExceptionSpecTokens = nullptr;
7303  ParsedAttributes FnAttrs(AttrFactory);
7304  TypeResult TrailingReturnType;
7305  SourceLocation TrailingReturnTypeLoc;
7306 
7307  /* LocalEndLoc is the end location for the local FunctionTypeLoc.
7308  EndLoc is the end location for the function declarator.
7309  They differ for trailing return types. */
7310  SourceLocation StartLoc, LocalEndLoc, EndLoc;
7311  SourceLocation LParenLoc, RParenLoc;
7312  LParenLoc = Tracker.getOpenLocation();
7313  StartLoc = LParenLoc;
7314 
7315  if (isFunctionDeclaratorIdentifierList()) {
7316  if (RequiresArg)
7317  Diag(Tok, diag::err_argument_required_after_attribute);
7318 
7319  ParseFunctionDeclaratorIdentifierList(D, ParamInfo);
7320 
7321  Tracker.consumeClose();
7322  RParenLoc = Tracker.getCloseLocation();
7323  LocalEndLoc = RParenLoc;
7324  EndLoc = RParenLoc;
7325 
7326  // If there are attributes following the identifier list, parse them and
7327  // prohibit them.
7328  MaybeParseCXX11Attributes(FnAttrs);
7329  ProhibitAttributes(FnAttrs);
7330  } else {
7331  if (Tok.isNot(tok::r_paren))
7332  ParseParameterDeclarationClause(D, FirstArgAttrs, ParamInfo, EllipsisLoc);
7333  else if (RequiresArg)
7334  Diag(Tok, diag::err_argument_required_after_attribute);
7335 
7336  // OpenCL disallows functions without a prototype, but it doesn't enforce
7337  // strict prototypes as in C23 because it allows a function definition to
7338  // have an identifier list. See OpenCL 3.0 6.11/g for more details.
7339  HasProto = ParamInfo.size() || getLangOpts().requiresStrictPrototypes() ||
7340  getLangOpts().OpenCL || getLangOpts().SYCLIsDevice;
7341 
7342  // If we have the closing ')', eat it.
7343  Tracker.consumeClose();
7344  RParenLoc = Tracker.getCloseLocation();
7345  LocalEndLoc = RParenLoc;
7346  EndLoc = RParenLoc;
7347 
7348  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus) {
7349  // FIXME: Accept these components in any order, and produce fixits to
7350  // correct the order if the user gets it wrong. Ideally we should deal
7351  // with the pure-specifier in the same way.
7352 
7353  // Parse cv-qualifier-seq[opt].
7354  ParseTypeQualifierListOpt(DS, AR_NoAttributesParsed,
7355  /*AtomicAllowed*/ false,
7356  /*IdentifierRequired=*/false,
7357  llvm::function_ref<void()>([&]() {
7358  Actions.CodeCompleteFunctionQualifiers(DS, D);
7359  }));
7360  if (!DS.getSourceRange().getEnd().isInvalid()) {
7361  EndLoc = DS.getSourceRange().getEnd();
7362  }
7363 
7364  // Parse ref-qualifier[opt].
7365  if (ParseRefQualifier(RefQualifierIsLValueRef, RefQualifierLoc))
7366  EndLoc = RefQualifierLoc;
7367 
7368  std::optional<Sema::CXXThisScopeRAII> ThisScope;
7369  InitCXXThisScopeForDeclaratorIfRelevant(D, DS, ThisScope);
7370 
7371  // Parse exception-specification[opt].
7372  // FIXME: Per [class.mem]p6, all exception-specifications at class scope
7373  // should be delayed, including those for non-members (eg, friend
7374  // declarations). But only applying this to member declarations is
7375  // consistent with what other implementations do.
7376  bool Delayed = D.isFirstDeclarationOfMember() &&
7377  D.isFunctionDeclaratorAFunctionDeclaration();
7378  if (Delayed && Actions.isLibstdcxxEagerExceptionSpecHack(D) &&
7379  GetLookAheadToken(0).is(tok::kw_noexcept) &&
7380  GetLookAheadToken(1).is(tok::l_paren) &&
7381  GetLookAheadToken(2).is(tok::kw_noexcept) &&
7382  GetLookAheadToken(3).is(tok::l_paren) &&
7383  GetLookAheadToken(4).is(tok::identifier) &&
7384  GetLookAheadToken(4).getIdentifierInfo()->isStr("swap")) {
7385  // HACK: We've got an exception-specification
7386  // noexcept(noexcept(swap(...)))
7387  // or
7388  // noexcept(noexcept(swap(...)) && noexcept(swap(...)))
7389  // on a 'swap' member function. This is a libstdc++ bug; the lookup
7390  // for 'swap' will only find the function we're currently declaring,
7391  // whereas it expects to find a non-member swap through ADL. Turn off
7392  // delayed parsing to give it a chance to find what it expects.
7393  Delayed = false;
7394  }
7395  ESpecType = tryParseExceptionSpecification(Delayed,
7396  ESpecRange,
7397  DynamicExceptions,
7398  DynamicExceptionRanges,
7399  NoexceptExpr,
7400  ExceptionSpecTokens);
7401  if (ESpecType != EST_None)
7402  EndLoc = ESpecRange.getEnd();
7403 
7404  // Parse attribute-specifier-seq[opt]. Per DR 979 and DR 1297, this goes
7405  // after the exception-specification.
7406  MaybeParseCXX11Attributes(FnAttrs);
7407 
7408  // Parse trailing-return-type[opt].
7409  LocalEndLoc = EndLoc;
7410  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 && Tok.is(tok::arrow)) {
7411  Diag(Tok, diag::warn_cxx98_compat_trailing_return_type);
7412  if (D.getDeclSpec().getTypeSpecType() == TST_auto)
7413  StartLoc = D.getDeclSpec().getTypeSpecTypeLoc();
7414  LocalEndLoc = Tok.getLocation();
7415  SourceRange Range;
7416  TrailingReturnType =
7417  ParseTrailingReturnType(Range, D.mayBeFollowedByCXXDirectInit());
7418  TrailingReturnTypeLoc = Range.getBegin();
7419  EndLoc = Range.getEnd();
7420  }
7421  } else {
7422  MaybeParseCXX11Attributes(FnAttrs);
7423  }
7424  }
7425 
7426  // Collect non-parameter declarations from the prototype if this is a function
7427  // declaration. They will be moved into the scope of the function. Only do
7428  // this in C and not C++, where the decls will continue to live in the
7429  // surrounding context.
7430  SmallVector<NamedDecl *, 0> DeclsInPrototype;
7431  if (getCurScope()->isFunctionDeclarationScope() && !getLangOpts().CPlusPlus) {
7432  for (Decl *D : getCurScope()->decls()) {
7433  NamedDecl *ND = dyn_cast<NamedDecl>(D);
7434  if (!ND || isa<ParmVarDecl>(ND))
7435  continue;
7436  DeclsInPrototype.push_back(ND);
7437  }
7438  // Sort DeclsInPrototype based on raw encoding of the source location.
7439  // Scope::decls() is iterating over a SmallPtrSet so sort the Decls before
7440  // moving to DeclContext. This provides a stable ordering for traversing
7441  // Decls in DeclContext, which is important for tasks like ASTWriter for
