7442  // deterministic output.
7443  llvm::sort(DeclsInPrototype, [](Decl *D1, Decl *D2) {
7444  return D1->getLocation().getRawEncoding() <
7445  D2->getLocation().getRawEncoding();
7446  });
7447  }
7448 
7449  // Remember that we parsed a function type, and remember the attributes.
7450  D.AddTypeInfo(DeclaratorChunk::getFunction(
7451  HasProto, IsAmbiguous, LParenLoc, ParamInfo.data(),
7452  ParamInfo.size(), EllipsisLoc, RParenLoc,
7453  RefQualifierIsLValueRef, RefQualifierLoc,
7454  /*MutableLoc=*/SourceLocation(),
7455  ESpecType, ESpecRange, DynamicExceptions.data(),
7456  DynamicExceptionRanges.data(), DynamicExceptions.size(),
7457  NoexceptExpr.isUsable() ? NoexceptExpr.get() : nullptr,
7458  ExceptionSpecTokens, DeclsInPrototype, StartLoc,
7459  LocalEndLoc, D, TrailingReturnType, TrailingReturnTypeLoc,
7460  &DS),
7461  std::move(FnAttrs), EndLoc);
7462 }
7463 
7464 /// ParseRefQualifier - Parses a member function ref-qualifier. Returns
7465 /// true if a ref-qualifier is found.
7466 bool Parser::ParseRefQualifier(bool &RefQualifierIsLValueRef,
7467  SourceLocation &RefQualifierLoc) {
7468  if (Tok.isOneOf(tok::amp, tok::ampamp)) {
7469  Diag(Tok, getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 ?
7470  diag::warn_cxx98_compat_ref_qualifier :
7471  diag::ext_ref_qualifier);
7472 
7473  RefQualifierIsLValueRef = Tok.is(tok::amp);
7474  RefQualifierLoc = ConsumeToken();
7475  return true;
7476  }
7477  return false;
7478 }
7479 
7480 /// isFunctionDeclaratorIdentifierList - This parameter list may have an
7481 /// identifier list form for a K&R-style function: void foo(a,b,c)
7482 ///
7483 /// Note that identifier-lists are only allowed for normal declarators, not for
7484 /// abstract-declarators.
7485 bool Parser::isFunctionDeclaratorIdentifierList() {
7486  return !getLangOpts().requiresStrictPrototypes()
7487  && Tok.is(tok::identifier)
7488  && !TryAltiVecVectorToken()
7489  // K&R identifier lists can't have typedefs as identifiers, per C99
7490  // 6.7.5.3p11.
7491  && (TryAnnotateTypeOrScopeToken() || !Tok.is(tok::annot_typename))
7492  // Identifier lists follow a really simple grammar: the identifiers can
7493  // be followed *only* by a ", identifier" or ")". However, K&R
7494  // identifier lists are really rare in the brave new modern world, and
7495  // it is very common for someone to typo a type in a non-K&R style
7496  // list. If we are presented with something like: "void foo(intptr x,
7497  // float y)", we don't want to start parsing the function declarator as
7498  // though it is a K&R style declarator just because intptr is an
7499  // invalid type.
7500  //
7501  // To handle this, we check to see if the token after the first
7502  // identifier is a "," or ")". Only then do we parse it as an
7503  // identifier list.
7504  && (!Tok.is(tok::eof) &&
7505  (NextToken().is(tok::comma) || NextToken().is(tok::r_paren)));
7506 }
7507 
7508 /// ParseFunctionDeclaratorIdentifierList - While parsing a function declarator
7509 /// we found a K&R-style identifier list instead of a typed parameter list.
7510 ///
7511 /// After returning, ParamInfo will hold the parsed parameters.
7512 ///
7513 /// identifier-list: [C99 6.7.5]
7514 /// identifier
7515 /// identifier-list ',' identifier
7516 ///
7517 void Parser::ParseFunctionDeclaratorIdentifierList(
7518  Declarator &D,
7519  SmallVectorImpl<DeclaratorChunk::ParamInfo> &ParamInfo) {
7520  // We should never reach this point in C23 or C++.
7521  assert(!getLangOpts().requiresStrictPrototypes() &&
7522  "Cannot parse an identifier list in C23 or C++");
7523 
7524  // If there was no identifier specified for the declarator, either we are in
7525  // an abstract-declarator, or we are in a parameter declarator which was found
7526  // to be abstract. In abstract-declarators, identifier lists are not valid:
7527  // diagnose this.
7528  if (!D.getIdentifier())
7529  Diag(Tok, diag::ext_ident_list_in_param);
7530 
7531  // Maintain an efficient lookup of params we have seen so far.
7532  llvm::SmallSet<const IdentifierInfo*, 16> ParamsSoFar;
7533 
7534  do {
7535  // If this isn't an identifier, report the error and skip until ')'.
7536  if (Tok.isNot(tok::identifier)) {
7537  Diag(Tok, diag::err_expected) << tok::identifier;
7538  SkipUntil(tok::r_paren, StopAtSemi | StopBeforeMatch);
7539  // Forget we parsed anything.
7540  ParamInfo.clear();
7541  return;
7542  }
7543 
7544  IdentifierInfo *ParmII = Tok.getIdentifierInfo();
7545 
7546  // Reject 'typedef int y; int test(x, y)', but continue parsing.
7547  if (Actions.getTypeName(*ParmII, Tok.getLocation(), getCurScope()))
7548  Diag(Tok, diag::err_unexpected_typedef_ident) << ParmII;
7549 
7550  // Verify that the argument identifier has not already been mentioned.
7551  if (!ParamsSoFar.insert(ParmII).second) {
7552  Diag(Tok, diag::err_param_redefinition) << ParmII;
7553  } else {
7554  // Remember this identifier in ParamInfo.
7555  ParamInfo.push_back(DeclaratorChunk::ParamInfo(ParmII,
7556  Tok.getLocation(),
7557  nullptr));
7558  }
7559 
7560  // Eat the identifier.
7561  ConsumeToken();
7562  // The list continues if we see a comma.
7563  } while (TryConsumeToken(tok::comma));
7564 }
7565 
7566 /// ParseParameterDeclarationClause - Parse a (possibly empty) parameter-list
7567 /// after the opening parenthesis. This function will not parse a K&R-style
7568 /// identifier list.
7569 ///
7570 /// DeclContext is the context of the declarator being parsed. If FirstArgAttrs
7571 /// is non-null, then the caller parsed those attributes immediately after the
7572 /// open paren - they will be applied to the DeclSpec of the first parameter.
7573 ///
7574 /// After returning, ParamInfo will hold the parsed parameters. EllipsisLoc will
7575 /// be the location of the ellipsis, if any was parsed.
7576 ///
7577 /// parameter-type-list: [C99 6.7.5]
7578 /// parameter-list
7579 /// parameter-list ',' '...'
7580 /// [C++] parameter-list '...'
7581 ///
7582 /// parameter-list: [C99 6.7.5]
7583 /// parameter-declaration
7584 /// parameter-list ',' parameter-declaration
7585 ///
7586 /// parameter-declaration: [C99 6.7.5]
7587 /// declaration-specifiers declarator
7588 /// [C++] declaration-specifiers declarator '=' assignment-expression
7589 /// [C++11] initializer-clause
7590 /// [GNU] declaration-specifiers declarator attributes
7591 /// declaration-specifiers abstract-declarator[opt]
7592 /// [C++] declaration-specifiers abstract-declarator[opt]
7593 /// '=' assignment-expression
7594 /// [GNU] declaration-specifiers abstract-declarator[opt] attributes
7595 /// [C++11] attribute-specifier-seq parameter-declaration
7596 /// [C++2b] attribute-specifier-seq 'this' parameter-declaration
7597 ///
7598 void Parser::ParseParameterDeclarationClause(
7599  DeclaratorContext DeclaratorCtx, ParsedAttributes &FirstArgAttrs,
7600  SmallVectorImpl<DeclaratorChunk::ParamInfo> &ParamInfo,
7601  SourceLocation &EllipsisLoc, bool IsACXXFunctionDeclaration) {
7602 
7603  // Avoid exceeding the maximum function scope depth.
7604  // See https://bugs.llvm.org/show_bug.cgi?id=19607
7605  // Note Sema::ActOnParamDeclarator calls ParmVarDecl::setScopeInfo with
7606  // getFunctionPrototypeDepth() - 1.
7607  if (getCurScope()->getFunctionPrototypeDepth() - 1 >
7608  ParmVarDecl::getMaxFunctionScopeDepth()) {
7609  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), diag::err_function_scope_depth_exceeded)
7610  << ParmVarDecl::getMaxFunctionScopeDepth();
7611  cutOffParsing();
7612  return;
7613  }
7614 
7615  // C++2a [temp.res]p5
7616  // A qualified-id is assumed to name a type if
7617  // - [...]
7618  // - it is a decl-specifier of the decl-specifier-seq of a
7619  // - [...]
7620  // - parameter-declaration in a member-declaration [...]
7621  // - parameter-declaration in a declarator of a function or function
7622  // template declaration whose declarator-id is qualified [...]
7623  // - parameter-declaration in a lambda-declarator [...]
7624  auto AllowImplicitTypename = ImplicitTypenameContext::No;
7625  if (DeclaratorCtx == DeclaratorContext::Member ||
7626  DeclaratorCtx == DeclaratorContext::LambdaExpr ||
7627  DeclaratorCtx == DeclaratorContext::RequiresExpr ||
7628  IsACXXFunctionDeclaration) {
7629  AllowImplicitTypename = ImplicitTypenameContext::Yes;
7630  }
7631 
7632  do {
7633  // FIXME: Issue a diagnostic if we parsed an attribute-specifier-seq
7634  // before deciding this was a parameter-declaration-clause.
7635  if (TryConsumeToken(tok::ellipsis, EllipsisLoc))
7636  break;
7637 
7638  // Parse the declaration-specifiers.
7639  // Just use the ParsingDeclaration "scope" of the declarator.
7640  DeclSpec DS(AttrFactory);
7641 
7642  ParsedAttributes ArgDeclAttrs(AttrFactory);
7643  ParsedAttributes ArgDeclSpecAttrs(AttrFactory);
7644 
7645  if (FirstArgAttrs.Range.isValid()) {
7646  // If the caller parsed attributes for the first argument, add them now.
7647  // Take them so that we only apply the attributes to the first parameter.
7648  // We have already started parsing the decl-specifier sequence, so don't
7649  // parse any parameter-declaration pieces that precede it.
7650  ArgDeclSpecAttrs.takeAllFrom(FirstArgAttrs);
7651  } else {
7652  // Parse any C++11 attributes.
7653  MaybeParseCXX11Attributes(ArgDeclAttrs);
7654 
7655  // Skip any Microsoft attributes before a param.
7656  MaybeParseMicrosoftAttributes(ArgDeclSpecAttrs);
7657  }
7658 
7659  SourceLocation DSStart = Tok.getLocation();
7660 
7661  // Parse a C++23 Explicit Object Parameter
7662  // We do that in all language modes to produce a better diagnostic.
7663  SourceLocation ThisLoc;
7664  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus && Tok.is(tok::kw_this)) {
7665  ThisLoc = ConsumeToken();
7666  // C++23 [dcl.fct]p6:
7667  // An explicit-object-parameter-declaration is a parameter-declaration
7668  // with a this specifier. An explicit-object-parameter-declaration
7669  // shall appear only as the first parameter-declaration of a
7670  // parameter-declaration-list of either:
7671  // - a member-declarator that declares a member function, or
7672  // - a lambda-declarator.
7673  //
7674  // The parameter-declaration-list of a requires-expression is not such
7675  // a context.
7676  if (DeclaratorCtx == DeclaratorContext::RequiresExpr)
7677  Diag(ThisLoc, diag::err_requires_expr_explicit_object_parameter);
7678  }
7679 
7680  ParseDeclarationSpecifiers(DS, /*TemplateInfo=*/ParsedTemplateInfo(),
7681  AS_none, DeclSpecContext::DSC_normal,
7682  /*LateAttrs=*/nullptr, AllowImplicitTypename);
7683 
7684  DS.takeAttributesFrom(ArgDeclSpecAttrs);
7685 
7686  // Parse the declarator. This is "PrototypeContext" or
7687  // "LambdaExprParameterContext", because we must accept either
7688  // 'declarator' or 'abstract-declarator' here.
7689  Declarator ParmDeclarator(DS, ArgDeclAttrs,
7690  DeclaratorCtx == DeclaratorContext::RequiresExpr
7691  ? DeclaratorContext::RequiresExpr
7692  : DeclaratorCtx == DeclaratorContext::LambdaExpr
7693  ? DeclaratorContext::LambdaExprParameter
7694  : DeclaratorContext::Prototype);
7695  ParseDeclarator(ParmDeclarator);
7696 
7697  if (ThisLoc.isValid())
7698  ParmDeclarator.SetRangeBegin(ThisLoc);
7699 
7700  // Parse GNU attributes, if present.
7701  MaybeParseGNUAttributes(ParmDeclarator);
7702  if (getLangOpts().HLSL)
7703  MaybeParseHLSLAnnotations(DS.getAttributes());
7704 
7705  if (Tok.is(tok::kw_requires)) {
7706  // User tried to define a requires clause in a parameter declaration,
7707  // which is surely not a function declaration.
7708  // void f(int (*g)(int, int) requires true);
7709  Diag(Tok,
7710  diag::err_requires_clause_on_declarator_not_declaring_a_function);
7711  ConsumeToken();
7712  Actions.CorrectDelayedTyposInExpr(
7713  ParseConstraintLogicalOrExpression(/*IsTrailingRequiresClause=*/true));
7714  }
7715 
7716  // Remember this parsed parameter in ParamInfo.
7717  const IdentifierInfo *ParmII = ParmDeclarator.getIdentifier();
7718 
7719  // DefArgToks is used when the parsing of default arguments needs
7720  // to be delayed.
7721  std::unique_ptr<CachedTokens> DefArgToks;
7722 
7723  // If no parameter was specified, verify that *something* was specified,
7724  // otherwise we have a missing type and identifier.
7725  if (DS.isEmpty() && ParmDeclarator.getIdentifier() == nullptr &&
7726  ParmDeclarator.getNumTypeObjects() == 0) {
7727  // Completely missing, emit error.
7728  Diag(DSStart, diag::err_missing_param);
7729  } else {
7730  // Otherwise, we have something. Add it and let semantic analysis try
7731  // to grok it and add the result to the ParamInfo we are building.
7732 
7733  // Last chance to recover from a misplaced ellipsis in an attempted
7734  // parameter pack declaration.
7735  if (Tok.is(tok::ellipsis) &&
7736  (NextToken().isNot(tok::r_paren) ||
7737  (!ParmDeclarator.getEllipsisLoc().isValid() &&
7738  !Actions.isUnexpandedParameterPackPermitted())) &&
7739  Actions.containsUnexpandedParameterPacks(ParmDeclarator))
7740  DiagnoseMisplacedEllipsisInDeclarator(ConsumeToken(), ParmDeclarator);
7741 
7742  // Now we are at the point where declarator parsing is finished.
7743  //
7744  // Try to catch keywords in place of the identifier in a declarator, and
7745  // in particular the common case where:
7746  // 1 identifier comes at the end of the declarator
7747  // 2 if the identifier is dropped, the declarator is valid but anonymous
7748  // (no identifier)
7749  // 3 declarator parsing succeeds, and then we have a trailing keyword,
7750  // which is never valid in a param list (e.g. missing a ',')
7751  // And we can't handle this in ParseDeclarator because in general keywords
7752  // may be allowed to follow the declarator. (And in some cases there'd be
7753  // better recovery like inserting punctuation). ParseDeclarator is just
7754  // treating this as an anonymous parameter, and fortunately at this point
7755  // we've already almost done that.
7756  //
7757  // We care about case 1) where the declarator type should be known, and
7758  // the identifier should be null.
7759  if (!ParmDeclarator.isInvalidType() && !ParmDeclarator.hasName() &&
7760  Tok.isNot(tok::raw_identifier) && !Tok.isAnnotation() &&
7761  Tok.getIdentifierInfo() &&
7762  Tok.getIdentifierInfo()->isKeyword(getLangOpts())) {
7763  Diag(Tok, diag::err_keyword_as_parameter) << PP.getSpelling(Tok);
7764  // Consume the keyword.
7765  ConsumeToken();
7766  }
7767  // Inform the actions module about the parameter declarator, so it gets
7768  // added to the current scope.
7769  Decl *Param =
7770  Actions.ActOnParamDeclarator(getCurScope(), ParmDeclarator, ThisLoc);
7771  // Parse the default argument, if any. We parse the default
7772  // arguments in all dialects; the semantic analysis in
7773  // ActOnParamDefaultArgument will reject the default argument in
7774  // C.
7775  if (Tok.is(tok::equal)) {
7776  SourceLocation EqualLoc = Tok.getLocation();
7777 
7778  // Parse the default argument
7779  if (DeclaratorCtx == DeclaratorContext::Member) {
7780  // If we're inside a class definition, cache the tokens
7781  // corresponding to the default argument. We'll actually parse
7782  // them when we see the end of the class definition.
7783  DefArgToks.reset(new CachedTokens);
7784 
7785  SourceLocation ArgStartLoc = NextToken().getLocation();
7786  ConsumeAndStoreInitializer(*DefArgToks, CIK_DefaultArgument);
7787  Actions.ActOnParamUnparsedDefaultArgument(Param, EqualLoc,
7788  ArgStartLoc);
7789  } else {
7790  // Consume the '='.
7791  ConsumeToken();
7792 
7793  // The argument isn't actually potentially evaluated unless it is
7794  // used.
7795  EnterExpressionEvaluationContext Eval(
7796  Actions,
7797  Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContext::PotentiallyEvaluatedIfUsed,
7798  Param);
7799 
7800  ExprResult DefArgResult;
7801  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 && Tok.is(tok::l_brace)) {
7802  Diag(Tok, diag::warn_cxx98_compat_generalized_initializer_lists);
7803  DefArgResult = ParseBraceInitializer();
7804  } else {
7805  if (Tok.is(tok::l_paren) && NextToken().is(tok::l_brace)) {
7806  Diag(Tok, diag::err_stmt_expr_in_default_arg) << 0;
7807  Actions.ActOnParamDefaultArgumentError(Param, EqualLoc,
7808  /*DefaultArg=*/nullptr);
7809  // Skip the statement expression and continue parsing
7810  SkipUntil(tok::comma, StopBeforeMatch);
7811  continue;
7812  }
7813  DefArgResult = ParseAssignmentExpression();
7814  }
7815  DefArgResult = Actions.CorrectDelayedTyposInExpr(DefArgResult);
7816  if (DefArgResult.isInvalid()) {
7817  Actions.ActOnParamDefaultArgumentError(Param, EqualLoc,
7818  /*DefaultArg=*/nullptr);
7819  SkipUntil(tok::comma, tok::r_paren, StopAtSemi | StopBeforeMatch);
7820  } else {
7821  // Inform the actions module about the default argument
7822  Actions.ActOnParamDefaultArgument(Param, EqualLoc,
7823  DefArgResult.get());
7824  }
7825  }
7826  }
7827 
7828  ParamInfo.push_back(DeclaratorChunk::ParamInfo(ParmII,
7829  ParmDeclarator.getIdentifierLoc(),
7830  Param, std::move(DefArgToks)));
7831  }
7832 
7833  if (TryConsumeToken(tok::ellipsis, EllipsisLoc)) {
7834  if (!getLangOpts().CPlusPlus) {
7835  // We have ellipsis without a preceding ',', which is ill-formed
7836  // in C. Complain and provide the fix.
7837  Diag(EllipsisLoc, diag::err_missing_comma_before_ellipsis)
7838  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(EllipsisLoc, ", ");
7839  } else if (ParmDeclarator.getEllipsisLoc().isValid() ||
7840  Actions.containsUnexpandedParameterPacks(ParmDeclarator)) {
7841  // It looks like this was supposed to be a parameter pack. Warn and
7842  // point out where the ellipsis should have gone.
7843  SourceLocation ParmEllipsis = ParmDeclarator.getEllipsisLoc();
7844  Diag(EllipsisLoc, diag::warn_misplaced_ellipsis_vararg)
7845  << ParmEllipsis.isValid() << ParmEllipsis;
7846  if (ParmEllipsis.isValid()) {
7847  Diag(ParmEllipsis,
7848  diag::note_misplaced_ellipsis_vararg_existing_ellipsis);
7849  } else {
7850  Diag(ParmDeclarator.getIdentifierLoc(),
7851  diag::note_misplaced_ellipsis_vararg_add_ellipsis)
7852  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(ParmDeclarator.getIdentifierLoc(),
7853  "...")
7854  << !ParmDeclarator.hasName();
7855  }
7856  Diag(EllipsisLoc, diag::note_misplaced_ellipsis_vararg_add_comma)
7857  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(EllipsisLoc, ", ");
7858  }
7859 
7860  // We can't have any more parameters after an ellipsis.
7861  break;
7862  }
7863 
7864  // If the next token is a comma, consume it and keep reading arguments.
7865  } while (TryConsumeToken(tok::comma));
7866 }
7867 
7868 /// [C90] direct-declarator '[' constant-expression[opt] ']'
7869 /// [C99] direct-declarator '[' type-qual-list[opt] assignment-expr[opt] ']'
7870 /// [C99] direct-declarator '[' 'static' type-qual-list[opt] assign-expr ']'
7871 /// [C99] direct-declarator '[' type-qual-list 'static' assignment-expr ']'
7872 /// [C99] direct-declarator '[' type-qual-list[opt] '*' ']'
7873 /// [C++11] direct-declarator '[' constant-expression[opt] ']'
7874 /// attribute-specifier-seq[opt]
7875 void Parser::ParseBracketDeclarator(Declarator &D) {
7876  if (CheckProhibitedCXX11Attribute())
7877  return;
7878 
7879  BalancedDelimiterTracker T(*this, tok::l_square);
7880  T.consumeOpen();
7881 
7882  // C array syntax has many features, but by-far the most common is [] and [4].
7883  // This code does a fast path to handle some of the most obvious cases.
7884  if (Tok.getKind() == tok::r_square) {
7885  T.consumeClose();
7886  ParsedAttributes attrs(AttrFactory);
7887  MaybeParseCXX11Attributes(attrs);
7888 
7889  // Remember that we parsed the empty array type.
7890  D.AddTypeInfo(DeclaratorChunk::getArray(0, false, false, nullptr,
7891  T.getOpenLocation(),
7892  T.getCloseLocation()),
7893  std::move(attrs), T.getCloseLocation());
7894  return;
7895  } else if (Tok.getKind() == tok::numeric_constant &&
7896  GetLookAheadToken(1).is(tok::r_square)) {
7897  // [4] is very common. Parse the numeric constant expression.
7898  ExprResult ExprRes(Actions.ActOnNumericConstant(Tok, getCurScope()));
7899  ConsumeToken();
7900 
7901  T.consumeClose();
7902  ParsedAttributes attrs(AttrFactory);
7903  MaybeParseCXX11Attributes(attrs);
7904 
7905  // Remember that we parsed a array type, and remember its features.
7906  D.AddTypeInfo(DeclaratorChunk::getArray(0, false, false, ExprRes.get(),
7907  T.getOpenLocation(),
7908  T.getCloseLocation()),
7909  std::move(attrs), T.getCloseLocation());
7910  return;
7911  } else if (Tok.getKind() == tok::code_completion) {
7912  cutOffParsing();
7913  Actions.CodeCompleteBracketDeclarator(getCurScope());
7914  return;
7915  }
7916 
7917  // If valid, this location is the position where we read the 'static' keyword.
7918  SourceLocation StaticLoc;
7919  TryConsumeToken(tok::kw_static, StaticLoc);
7920 
7921  // If there is a type-qualifier-list, read it now.
7922  // Type qualifiers in an array subscript are a C99 feature.
7923  DeclSpec DS(AttrFactory);
7924  ParseTypeQualifierListOpt(DS, AR_CXX11AttributesParsed);
7925 
7926  // If we haven't already read 'static', check to see if there is one after the
7927  // type-qualifier-list.
7928  if (!StaticLoc.isValid())
7929  TryConsumeToken(tok::kw_static, StaticLoc);
7930 
7931  // Handle "direct-declarator [ type-qual-list[opt] * ]".
7932  bool isStar = false;
7933  ExprResult NumElements;
7934 
7935  // Handle the case where we have '[*]' as the array size. However, a leading
7936  // star could be the start of an expression, for example 'X[*p + 4]'. Verify
7937  // the token after the star is a ']'. Since stars in arrays are
7938  // infrequent, use of lookahead is not costly here.
7939  if (Tok.is(tok::star) && GetLookAheadToken(1).is(tok::r_square)) {
7940  ConsumeToken(); // Eat the '*'.
7941 
7942  if (StaticLoc.isValid()) {
7943  Diag(StaticLoc, diag::err_unspecified_vla_size_with_static);
7944  StaticLoc = SourceLocation(); // Drop the static.
7945  }
7946  isStar = true;
7947  } else if (Tok.isNot(tok::r_square)) {
7948  // Note, in C89, this production uses the constant-expr production instead
7949  // of assignment-expr. The only difference is that assignment-expr allows
7950  // things like '=' and '*='. Sema rejects these in C89 mode because they
7951  // are not i-c-e's, so we don't need to distinguish between the two here.
7952 
7953  // Parse the constant-expression or assignment-expression now (depending
7954  // on dialect).
7955  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus) {
7956  NumElements = ParseArrayBoundExpression();
7957  } else {
7958  EnterExpressionEvaluationContext Unevaluated(
7959  Actions, Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContext::ConstantEvaluated);
7960  NumElements =
7961  Actions.CorrectDelayedTyposInExpr(ParseAssignmentExpression());
7962  }
7963  } else {
7964  if (StaticLoc.isValid()) {
7965  Diag(StaticLoc, diag::err_unspecified_size_with_static);
7966  StaticLoc = SourceLocation(); // Drop the static.
7967  }
7968  }
7969 
7970  // If there was an error parsing the assignment-expression, recover.
7971  if (NumElements.isInvalid()) {
7972  D.setInvalidType(true);
7973  // If the expression was invalid, skip it.
7974  SkipUntil(tok::r_square, StopAtSemi);
7975  return;
7976  }
7977 
7978  T.consumeClose();
7979 
7980  MaybeParseCXX11Attributes(DS.getAttributes());
7981 
7982  // Remember that we parsed a array type, and remember its features.
7983  D.AddTypeInfo(
7984  DeclaratorChunk::getArray(DS.getTypeQualifiers(), StaticLoc.isValid(),
7985  isStar, NumElements.get(), T.getOpenLocation(),
7986  T.getCloseLocation()),
7987  std::move(DS.getAttributes()), T.getCloseLocation());
7988 }
7989 
7990 /// Diagnose brackets before an identifier.
7991 void Parser::ParseMisplacedBracketDeclarator(Declarator &D) {
7992  assert(Tok.is(tok::l_square) && "Missing opening bracket");
7993  assert(!D.mayOmitIdentifier() && "Declarator cannot omit identifier");
7994 
7995  SourceLocation StartBracketLoc = Tok.getLocation();
7996  Declarator TempDeclarator(D.getDeclSpec(), ParsedAttributesView::none(),
7997  D.getContext());
7998 
7999  while (Tok.is(tok::l_square)) {
8000  ParseBracketDeclarator(TempDeclarator);
8001  }
8002 
8003  // Stuff the location of the start of the brackets into the Declarator.
8004  // The diagnostics from ParseDirectDeclarator will make more sense if
8005  // they use this location instead.
8006  if (Tok.is(tok::semi))
8007  D.getName().EndLocation = StartBracketLoc;
8008 
8009  SourceLocation SuggestParenLoc = Tok.getLocation();
8010 
8011  // Now that the brackets are removed, try parsing the declarator again.
8012  ParseDeclaratorInternal(D, &Parser::ParseDirectDeclarator);
8013 
8014  // Something went wrong parsing the brackets, in which case,
8015  // ParseBracketDeclarator has emitted an error, and we don't need to emit
8016  // one here.
8017  if (TempDeclarator.getNumTypeObjects() == 0)
8018  return;
8019 
8020  // Determine if parens will need to be suggested in the diagnostic.
8021  bool NeedParens = false;
8022  if (D.getNumTypeObjects() != 0) {
8023  switch (D.getTypeObject(D.getNumTypeObjects() - 1).Kind) {
8024  case DeclaratorChunk::Pointer:
8025  case DeclaratorChunk::Reference:
8026  case DeclaratorChunk::BlockPointer:
8027  case DeclaratorChunk::MemberPointer:
8028  case DeclaratorChunk::Pipe:
8029  NeedParens = true;
8030  break;
8031  case DeclaratorChunk::Array:
8032  case DeclaratorChunk::Function:
8033  case DeclaratorChunk::Paren:
8034  break;
8035  }
8036  }
8037 
8038  if (NeedParens) {
8039  // Create a DeclaratorChunk for the inserted parens.
8040  SourceLocation EndLoc = PP.getLocForEndOfToken(D.getEndLoc());
8041  D.AddTypeInfo(DeclaratorChunk::getParen(SuggestParenLoc, EndLoc),
8042  SourceLocation());
8043  }
8044 
8045  // Adding back the bracket info to the end of the Declarator.
8046  for (unsigned i = 0, e = TempDeclarator.getNumTypeObjects(); i < e; ++i) {
8047  const DeclaratorChunk &Chunk = TempDeclarator.getTypeObject(i);
8048  D.AddTypeInfo(Chunk, TempDeclarator.getAttributePool(), SourceLocation());
8049  }
8050 
8051  // The missing identifier would have been diagnosed in ParseDirectDeclarator.
8052  // If parentheses are required, always suggest them.
8053  if (!D.getIdentifier() && !NeedParens)
8054  return;
8055 
8056  SourceLocation EndBracketLoc = TempDeclarator.getEndLoc();
8057 
8058  // Generate the move bracket error message.
8059  SourceRange BracketRange(StartBracketLoc, EndBracketLoc);
8060  SourceLocation EndLoc = PP.getLocForEndOfToken(D.getEndLoc());
8061 
8062  if (NeedParens) {
8063  Diag(EndLoc, diag::err_brackets_go_after_unqualified_id)
8064  << getLangOpts().CPlusPlus
8065  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(SuggestParenLoc, "(")
8066  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(EndLoc, ")")
8067  << FixItHint::CreateInsertionFromRange(
8068  EndLoc, CharSourceRange(BracketRange, true))
8069  << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(BracketRange);
8070  } else {
8071  Diag(EndLoc, diag::err_brackets_go_after_unqualified_id)
8072  << getLangOpts().CPlusPlus
8073  << FixItHint::CreateInsertionFromRange(
8074  EndLoc, CharSourceRange(BracketRange, true))
8075  << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(BracketRange);
8076  }
8077 }
8078 
8079 /// [GNU] typeof-specifier:
8080 /// typeof ( expressions )
8081 /// typeof ( type-name )
8082 /// [GNU/C++] typeof unary-expression
8083 /// [C23] typeof-specifier:
8084 /// typeof '(' typeof-specifier-argument ')'
8085 /// typeof_unqual '(' typeof-specifier-argument ')'
8086 ///
8087 /// typeof-specifier-argument:
8088 /// expression
8089 /// type-name
8090 ///
8091 void Parser::ParseTypeofSpecifier(DeclSpec &DS) {
8092  assert(Tok.isOneOf(tok::kw_typeof, tok::kw_typeof_unqual) &&
8093  "Not a typeof specifier");
8094 
8095  bool IsUnqual = Tok.is(tok::kw_typeof_unqual);
8096  const IdentifierInfo *II = Tok.getIdentifierInfo();
8097  if (getLangOpts().C23 && !II->getName().starts_with("__"))
8098  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), diag::warn_c23_compat_keyword) << Tok.getName();
8099 
8100  Token OpTok = Tok;
8101  SourceLocation StartLoc = ConsumeToken();
8102  bool HasParens = Tok.is(tok::l_paren);
8103 
8104  EnterExpressionEvaluationContext Unevaluated(
8105  Actions, Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContext::Unevaluated,
8106  Sema::ReuseLambdaContextDecl);
8107 
8108  bool isCastExpr;
8109  ParsedType CastTy;
8110  SourceRange CastRange;
8111  ExprResult Operand = Actions.CorrectDelayedTyposInExpr(
8112  ParseExprAfterUnaryExprOrTypeTrait(OpTok, isCastExpr, CastTy, CastRange));
8113  if (HasParens)
8114  DS.setTypeArgumentRange(CastRange);
8115 
8116  if (CastRange.getEnd().isInvalid())
8117  // FIXME: Not accurate, the range gets one token more than it should.
8118  DS.SetRangeEnd(Tok.getLocation());
8119  else
8120  DS.SetRangeEnd(CastRange.getEnd());
8121 
8122  if (isCastExpr) {
8123  if (!CastTy) {
8124  DS.SetTypeSpecError();
8125  return;
8126  }
8127 
8128  const char *PrevSpec = nullptr;
8129  unsigned DiagID;
8130  // Check for duplicate type specifiers (e.g. "int typeof(int)").
8131  if (DS.SetTypeSpecType(IsUnqual ? DeclSpec::TST_typeof_unqualType
8132  : DeclSpec::TST_typeofType,
8133  StartLoc, PrevSpec,
8134  DiagID, CastTy,
8135  Actions.getASTContext().getPrintingPolicy()))
8136  Diag(StartLoc, DiagID) << PrevSpec;
8137  return;
8138  }
8139 
8140  // If we get here, the operand to the typeof was an expression.
8141  if (Operand.isInvalid()) {
8142  DS.SetTypeSpecError();
8143  return;
8144  }
8145 
8146  // We might need to transform the operand if it is potentially evaluated.
8147  Operand = Actions.HandleExprEvaluationContextForTypeof(Operand.get());
8148  if (Operand.isInvalid()) {
8149  DS.SetTypeSpecError();
8150  return;
8151  }
8152 
8153  const char *PrevSpec = nullptr;
8154  unsigned DiagID;
8155  // Check for duplicate type specifiers (e.g. "int typeof(int)").
8156  if (DS.SetTypeSpecType(IsUnqual ? DeclSpec::TST_typeof_unqualExpr
8157  : DeclSpec::TST_typeofExpr,
8158  StartLoc, PrevSpec,
8159  DiagID, Operand.get(),
8160  Actions.getASTContext().getPrintingPolicy()))
8161  Diag(StartLoc, DiagID) << PrevSpec;
8162 }
8163 
8164 /// [C11] atomic-specifier:
8165 /// _Atomic ( type-name )
8166 ///
8167 void Parser::ParseAtomicSpecifier(DeclSpec &DS) {
8168  assert(Tok.is(tok::kw__Atomic) && NextToken().is(tok::l_paren) &&
8169  "Not an atomic specifier");
8170 
8171  SourceLocation StartLoc = ConsumeToken();
8172  BalancedDelimiterTracker T(*this, tok::l_paren);
8173  if (T.consumeOpen())
8174  return;
8175 
8176  TypeResult Result = ParseTypeName();
8177  if (Result.isInvalid()) {
8178  SkipUntil(tok::r_paren, StopAtSemi);
8179  return;
8180  }
8181 
8182  // Match the ')'
8183  T.consumeClose();
8184 
8185  if (T.getCloseLocation().isInvalid())
8186  return;
8187 
8188  DS.setTypeArgumentRange(T.getRange());
8189  DS.SetRangeEnd(T.getCloseLocation());
8190 
8191  const char *PrevSpec = nullptr;
8192  unsigned DiagID;
8193  if (DS.SetTypeSpecType(DeclSpec::TST_atomic, StartLoc, PrevSpec,
8194  DiagID, Result.get(),
8195  Actions.getASTContext().getPrintingPolicy()))
8196  Diag(StartLoc, DiagID) << PrevSpec;
8197 }
8198 
8199 /// TryAltiVecVectorTokenOutOfLine - Out of line body that should only be called
8200 /// from TryAltiVecVectorToken.
8201 bool Parser::TryAltiVecVectorTokenOutOfLine() {
8202  Token Next = NextToken();
8203  switch (Next.getKind()) {
8204  default: return false;
8205  case tok::kw_short:
8206  case tok::kw_long:
8207  case tok::kw_signed:
8208  case tok::kw_unsigned:
8209  case tok::kw_void:
8210  case tok::kw_char:
8211  case tok::kw_int:
8212  case tok::kw_float:
8213  case tok::kw_double:
8214  case tok::kw_bool:
8215  case tok::kw__Bool:
8216  case tok::kw___bool:
8217  case tok::kw___pixel:
8218  Tok.setKind(tok::kw___vector);
8219  return true;
8220  case tok::identifier:
8221  if (Next.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_pixel) {
8222  Tok.setKind(tok::kw___vector);
8223  return true;
8224  }
8225  if (Next.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_bool ||
8226  Next.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_Bool) {
8227  Tok.setKind(tok::kw___vector);
8228  return true;
8229  }
8230  return false;
8231  }
8232 }
8233 
8234 bool Parser::TryAltiVecTokenOutOfLine(DeclSpec &DS, SourceLocation Loc,
8235  const char *&PrevSpec, unsigned &DiagID,
8236  bool &isInvalid) {
8237  const PrintingPolicy &Policy = Actions.getASTContext().getPrintingPolicy();
8238  if (Tok.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_vector) {
8239  Token Next = NextToken();
8240  switch (Next.getKind()) {
8241  case tok::kw_short:
8242  case tok::kw_long:
8243  case tok::kw_signed:
8244  case tok::kw_unsigned:
8245  case tok::kw_void:
8246  case tok::kw_char:
8247  case tok::kw_int:
8248  case tok::kw_float:
8249  case tok::kw_double:
8250  case tok::kw_bool:
8251  case tok::kw__Bool:
8252  case tok::kw___bool:
8253  case tok::kw___pixel:
8254  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeAltiVecVector(true, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID, Policy);
8255  return true;
8256  case tok::identifier:
8257  if (Next.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_pixel) {
8258  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeAltiVecVector(true, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID,Policy);
8259  return true;
8260  }
8261  if (Next.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_bool ||
8262  Next.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_Bool) {
8263  isInvalid =
8264  DS.SetTypeAltiVecVector(true, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID, Policy);
8265  return true;
8266  }
8267  break;
8268  default:
8269  break;
8270  }
8271  } else if ((Tok.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_pixel) &&
8272  DS.isTypeAltiVecVector()) {
8273  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeAltiVecPixel(true, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID, Policy);
8274  return true;
8275  } else if ((Tok.getIdentifierInfo() == Ident_bool) &&
8276  DS.isTypeAltiVecVector()) {
8277  isInvalid = DS.SetTypeAltiVecBool(true, Loc, PrevSpec, DiagID, Policy);
8278  return true;
8279  }
8280  return false;
8281 }
8282 
8283 TypeResult Parser::ParseTypeFromString(StringRef TypeStr, StringRef Context,
8284  SourceLocation IncludeLoc) {
8285  // Consume (unexpanded) tokens up to the end-of-directive.
8286  SmallVector<Token, 4> Tokens;
8287  {
8288  // Create a new buffer from which we will parse the type.
8289  auto &SourceMgr = PP.getSourceManager();
8290  FileID FID = SourceMgr.createFileID(
8291  llvm::MemoryBuffer::getMemBufferCopy(TypeStr, Context), SrcMgr::C_User,
8292  0, 0, IncludeLoc);
8293 
8294  // Form a new lexer that references the buffer.
8295  Lexer L(FID, SourceMgr.getBufferOrFake(FID), PP);
8296  L.setParsingPreprocessorDirective(true);
8297 
8298  // Lex the tokens from that buffer.
8299  Token Tok;
8300  do {
8301  L.Lex(Tok);
8302  Tokens.push_back(Tok);
8303  } while (Tok.isNot(tok::eod));
8304  }
8305 
8306  // Replace the "eod" token with an "eof" token identifying the end of
8307  // the provided string.
8308  Token &EndToken = Tokens.back();
8309  EndToken.startToken();
8310  EndToken.setKind(tok::eof);
8311  EndToken.setLocation(Tok.getLocation());
8312  EndToken.setEofData(TypeStr.data());
8313 
8314  // Add the current token back.
8315  Tokens.push_back(Tok);
8316 
8317  // Enter the tokens into the token stream.
8318  PP.EnterTokenStream(Tokens, /*DisableMacroExpansion=*/false,
8319  /*IsReinject=*/false);
8320 
8321  // Consume the current token so that we'll start parsing the tokens we
8322  // added to the stream.
8323  ConsumeAnyToken();
8324 
8325  // Enter a new scope.
8326  ParseScope LocalScope(this, 0);
8327 
8328  // Parse the type.
8329  TypeResult Result = ParseTypeName(nullptr);
8330 
8331  // Check if we parsed the whole thing.
8332  if (Result.isUsable() &&
8333  (Tok.isNot(tok::eof) || Tok.getEofData() != TypeStr.data())) {
8334  Diag(Tok.getLocation(), diag::err_type_unparsed);
8335  }
8336 
8337  // There could be leftover tokens (e.g. because of an error).
8338  // Skip through until we reach the 'end of directive' token.
8339  while (Tok.isNot(tok::eof))
8340  ConsumeAnyToken();
8341 
8342  // Consume the end token.
8343  if (Tok.is(tok::eof) && Tok.getEofData() == TypeStr.data())
8344  ConsumeAnyToken();
8345  return Result;
8346 }
8347 
8348 void Parser::DiagnoseBitIntUse(const Token &Tok) {
8349  // If the token is for _ExtInt, diagnose it as being deprecated. Otherwise,
8350  // the token is about _BitInt and gets (potentially) diagnosed as use of an
8351  // extension.
8352  assert(Tok.isOneOf(tok::kw__ExtInt, tok::kw__BitInt) &&
8353  "expected either an _ExtInt or _BitInt token!");
8354 
8355  SourceLocation Loc = Tok.getLocation();
8356  if (Tok.is(tok::kw__ExtInt)) {
8357  Diag(Loc, diag::warn_ext_int_deprecated)
8358  << FixItHint::CreateReplacement(Loc, "_BitInt");
8359  } else {
8360  // In C23 mode, diagnose that the use is not compatible with pre-C23 modes.
8361  // Otherwise, diagnose that the use is a Clang extension.
8362  if (getLangOpts().C23)
8363  Diag(Loc, diag::warn_c23_compat_keyword) << Tok.getName();
8364  else
8365  Diag(Loc, diag::ext_bit_int) << getLangOpts().CPlusPlus;
8366  }
8367 }
